column168: CAR OVERLOADED - CAR COOLED AND SWITCHED INTO CONSIGNEE FACILITY.

WE WERE DELIVERING A LOAD OF 7500 GALLONS OF FUEL (#2 DIESEL) TO A LOCATION HAVINF 3 ABOVE GROUND STORAGE TANKS, EACH WITH A CAPACITY OF 12,000 GALLONS.  WE RECEIVED ADVISE FROM THE PERSON ON DUTY WITH WESTERN PAVING TO UNLOAD PRODUCT INTO TANK NUMBER 1.  WE FOLLOWED THOSE INSTRUCTIONS BUT BEFORE UNLOADING WAS COMPLETE TANK NUMBER 1 OVERFLOWED SPILLING BETWEEN 75 AND 100 GALLONS OF PRODUCT INTO CONTAINMENT AREA.  THE SPILL WAS CONFINED TO THE STORAGE TANK CONTAINMENT AREA AND WAS ABSORBED BY SOME ABSORBANT PADS WHICH WERE APPLIED TO THE SPILL AREA.  THE ABSORBANT MATERIAL WILL BE DISPOSED OF IN ACCORDANCE WITH ENVIRONMENTAL REGULATIONS BY WESTERN PAVING.  THE STORAGE TANKS INVOLVED HAVE NO MEANS FOR GAUGING OR CHECKING FOR OUTAGE AND ARE FILLED DURING DELIVERIES ON INSTRUCTION FROM WESTERN PAVING PERSONNEL.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: THE PAILS WERE DOUBLE STACKED ON PALLETS. DOCKWORKER WAS UNLOADING USING A FORK LIFT.  WHEN HE EXITED THE TRAILER TWO OF THE PAILS FELL OF THE PALLET. ONE LANDED ON THE DOCK AND DIDN'T RUPTURE AND THE OTHER FELL OFF THE DOCK ONTO THE PARKING LOT AND RUPTURED.  THE CHEMICAL CAME IN CONTACT ONLY WITH THE CONCRETE PAD.  THE IMMEDIATE AREA WAS CLEARED OF ALL PERSONELL. ALICIA WIHT MONARCH CO.  WAS CONTACTED FOR EMERGENCY RESPONSE INSTRUCTIONS.  SHE ADVISED MYSELF OF THE PROPER METHOD OF CLEAN-UP.  LIME WAS USED TO NEUTRALIZE THE CHEMICAL, THE EXCESS WAS DISPOSED OF THEN THE ENTIRE AREA WAS FLUSHED WITH WATER.

column168: DRIVER WAS INSTRUCTED AS TO WHAT STORAGE TANK TO UNLOAD INTO.  DRIVER ALSO GOT OKAY TO UNLOAD.  AFTER UNLOADING 4000 GALLONS, THEIR STORAGE TANK OVERFLOWED ONTO A CONCRETE PAD.  SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND BALANCE OF LOAD (2000 GALLONS) WAS UNLOADED INTO ANOTHER STORAGE TANK.  CONSIGNEE INFORMED DRIVER THEY WOULD CLEAN AREA UP.
TANK CAR DERAILED UPRIGHT, WHEELS OFF TRACK.  PLUG IN SAMPLE VALVE LOOSE. TIGHTENED PLUG STOPPED VAPOR LEAK.  TANK CAR DERAILED AT 1745 HOURS, NO LEAKAGE.

FUMES WERE NOTED AS CREW WORKED NEAR THIS CAR.  DUE TO HOT, HUMID WEATHER, HYDROCHLORIC ACID FUMES WERE COMING THROUGH HOLE WHERE SAFETY VENT DISK WAS MISSING.  CONSIGNEE RESPONDED AND PLACED DISK IN THE ASSEMBLY.

TRAIN CREW NOTICED VAPORS AND SMELLED FUMES IN VICINITY OF CAR.  CAR WAS ISOLATED FOR SHIPPER'S INSPECTION.  INSPECTION REVEALED NO SAFETY VENT DISK IN PLACE.  DISK WAS PLACED IN ASSEMBLY AND CAR RETURNED TO TRANSPORTATION.

column168: CAR OBSERVED LEAKING DRUING CLASSIFICATION.  CAR ISOLATED UNTIL SHIPPER RESPONSE TEAM REPAIRED FOLLOWING DAY; REPAIR CONSISTED OF SAFETY VENT DISK REPLACEMENT.
LOW PRESSURE REGULATOR OPENED TO REDUCE INTERNAL PRESSURE, THEN FROZE IN OPEN POSITION.  SHIPPER RESPONDED TO REDUCE PRESSURE, AND THAW REGULATOR.

CAR OBSERVED FUMING DURING CLASSIFICATION ACTIVITY.  CAR ISOLATED AND CONSIGNEE RESPONDED.  SAFETY VENT DISK WAS REPLACED ON THE CAR AND CAR RETURNED TO TRANSPORTATION (CONSIGNEE RESPONDED FROM THEODORE, AL).

SKID OF PLASTIC PAILS WAS APPARENTLY SHRINKWRAPPED TOO TIGHTLY, CAUSING SEVERAL LIDS TO LOOSEN ON CONTAINERS AND VAPORS TO ESCAPE.  EMERGENCY RESPONSE PHONE NUMBER, CHEMTREC AND CHEMTRON (CANADA) WERE CONTACTED.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AND CLOSED THE ROAD UNTIL THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR ARRIVED.  HERITAGE ENVIRONMENTAL FOUND NO SPILLED MATERIAL. TWO EMPLOYEES CONPLAINED OF FUMES AND WERE CHECKED ON-SITE.  NO MEDICAL TREATMENT WAS NECESSARY AND NO FOLLOWUP OR TIME LOST FROM WORK.

LOADING FROM STEEL DRUM INTO THE TANKS.  HOSE SLIPPED OUT OF TANK CAUSING SPILLAGE.

A PINHOLE LEAK ON BOTTOM OF DRUM WAS DETECTED ON ARRIVAL AT PRESTON'S CLEVELAND OHIO SERVICE CENTER.  A NEW DRUM WAS FURNISH BY THE SHIPPER WITH THE PRODUCT BEING TRANSFERRED INTO THE NEW CONTAINER.  DELIVERED TO CUSTOMER WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

column168: 1) SOLVENT & BLAND MADE IN DRUMS.  2)  BUNGS TIGHTENED AND MOVED TO SHIPPING AREA AT FRONT OF PLANT.  3) OBSERVED LIQUID ON TOP OF DRUM. 4)  ATTEMPTED TO TIGHTEN LARGE BUNG.  5) THEN OBSERVED LEAK AROUND FLANGE AT TOP OF DRUM.  6) MATERIAL REDRUMMED.  7) DEFECTIVE DRUM RETURNED TO CINCINNATI DRUM SERVICE.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: ON 7/03/1991 TRAILER 515-9216 ARRIVED IN FRESNO CA.  FROM SACRAMENTO CA. WHEN TRAILER WAS BACKED TO THE DOCK AND THE DOOR WAS OPENED A YELLOW SUBSTANCE BEGAN TO RUN OUT.  THE DOOR WAS CLOSED AND THE FREIGHT BILL, PRO 847-620616, WAS CHECKED FOR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  THE SUBSTANCE WAS YELLOW PRINTER'S INK AND WAS NOT LISTED AS A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  THE CONTAINER, A 7 FOOT HIGH TOTE HAD FALLEN OVER IN ROUTE FROM SACRAMANTO CA. TO FRESNO CA. AND SPILLED INSIDE THE TRAILER, AND NONE OF IT LEAKED OUT.  THE TOTE WAS LOADED ON THE LEFT SIDE AND REAR OF THE TRAILER AND WAS NOT SECURED IN ANY WAY.  A CONTAINMENT AREA WAS MADE USING ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND SAND AND CARDBOARD.  THE INK RAN OUT INTO THE CONTAINMENT AREA.  WE CONTACTED SEVERAL H.M. CLEAN-UP CREWS TO GET ESTIMATES ON WHAT IT WOULD COST TO CLEAN-UP.  ERICKSON HAZ-MAT SERVICES IS NOW CLEANING UP SPILL.  THEIR ADDRESS IS 2953 S EAST AVE. FRESNO CA.  93706 PH# 209-266-9005.  MSDS SHEETS WERE GONE OVER WITH EACH EMPLOYEE THAT WAS NEAR OR CAME IN CONTACT WITH THE INK.  NONE OF THE EMPLOYEES COMPLAINED OF ANY SYMPTOMS.  IN THE FUTURE EMPLOYEES ARE TO MAKE SURE THAT ALL THEIR FREIGHT IS SECURED WHICH HAS ALWAYS BEEN COMPANY POLICY.  ERICKSON WILL BE DISPOSING OF THE WASTE IN AN APPROVED DISPOSAL SITE.

THREE DRUMS OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID WERE STORED ON THE TRUCK FOR SHIPMENT. APPARENTLY THE BINDINGS SLIPPED ON ONE OF THE DRUMS AND IT FELL FROM THE TRUCK.  THE DRUM BROKE OPEN UPON IMPACT WITH ROAD SURFACE.  OUR COMPANY DISPATCHED A CREW WHICH NEUTRALIZED THE MATERIAL WITHIN I HOUR OF ARRIVAL AT THE INCIDENT.  NO ENVIRONMENTAL OR PROPERTY DAMAGE ACCURED.  WE WILL BE USING A NEW-TYPE OF BINDING WHICH SHOULD PREVENT A RE-OCCURANCE OF THIS TYPE OF INCIDENT.
DOCKWORKER DAMAGED ONE CARTON WITH FORKLIFT BLADES DURING LOADING.  ALL SPILLAGE EVAPORATED IMMEDIATELY.  THE EMPTY BOTTLE WAS PLACED INTO A RECOVERY PAIL AND IS BEING HELD FOR DISPOSAL.

DOCKWORKER NOTICED A CARTON LEAKING ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER.  THE AREA WAS ISOLATED AND THE SHIPPING PAPER WERE SECURED TO DETERMINE THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED AND THE DOT EMERGENCY RESPONSE GUIDEBOOK WAS USED TO DETERMINE CLEANUP PROCEDURE.  SHIPPER ADVISED DAMAGED FREIGHT AND ALL CLEANUP MATERIAL WERE TO BE RETURNED TO SHIPPER FOR DISPOSITION.

column42: AMMONIA SOLUTION, RELATIVE DENSITY BETWEEN 0.880 AND 0.957 AT 15 DEGREES C IN WATER, WITH MORE THAN 10 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 35 PERCENT AMMONIA
column168: WHILE DOCKWORKER WAS REMOVING OTHER FREIGHT FROM TRAILER, HE NOTICED AN ODOR.  UPON INVESTIGATION, HE FOUND ONE CARTON THAT HAD FALLEN AND BROKEN THE INNER CONTAINER.  THE MATERAIL WAS IDENTIFIED AND THE DAMAGED CARTON WAS PLACED INSIDE A RECOVERY PAIL.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED.

WHILE UNLOADING TRAILER, DOCKWORKER DISCOVERED WET DUNNAGE ON THE FLOOR AND FOUND A DRUM THAT HAD BEEN PUSHED IN, CAUSING A SMALL CRACK IN THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM.  THE AREA WAS ISOLATED AND THE MATERIAL IDENTIFIED.  CHEMTREC WAS CALLED AND ADVISED NEUTRALIZATION.  THE DRUM WAS PATCHED AND PLACED INSIDE AN OVERPACK DRUM FOR FORWARDING TO DESTINATION.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Abrasion; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: ONE CARTON WAS APPRENTLY PUNCTURED BY ADJACENT FREIGHT, CAUSING THE INNER CONTAINER TO BREAK OPEN AND SPILL ITS CONTENTS INTO THE CARTON.  THE BROKEN BOTTLE WAS PLACED IN A PLASTIC BAG AND PUT INSIDE A FIBER DRUM FOR FORWARDING TO DESTINATION.

DOCKWORKER NOTICED A SMALL AMOUNT OF SPILLAGE DURING UNLOADING AND FOUND A PINHOLE IN ONE DRUM.  THE DRUM WAS PLACED INSIDE A RECOVERY DRUM AND FORWARDED.  ALL SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED USING ABSORBENTS.

WHEN SHIPMENT WAS RECEIVED AT TERMINAL, DOCKWORKER NOTICED AMALL PUNCTURES IN THREE BAGS AND FOUND A SMALL SMOUNT OF MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED.  USING PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT, THE SPILLAGE WAS CLEANED UP AND THE DAMAGED BAGS FORWARDED INSIDE RECOVERY DRUMS.

DOCKWORKER FOUND ONE CARTON WITH A WET BOTTOM AND OPENED THE CARTON TO FIND ONE INNER CONTAINER HAD LEAKED MATERIAL FROM THE LID.  THE MATERIAL HAD APPARENTLY ALSO LEAKED THROUGH THE INNER LINER TO THE SOAKED CARTON. CHEMTREC WAS CALLED AND CLEANUP WAS PERFORMED AS ADVISED.  ALL SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP AND THE LIDS TIGHTENED.  THE BOTTLES WERE REPACKED INTO A NEW CARTON AND ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIALS WERE SEALED INSIDE A RECOVERY PACK.

column168: PLASTIC DRUMS HAD BUNGS NOT TIGHTENED SECURELY, ALLOWING SOME SEEPAGE TO OCCUR.  THE AREA WAS ISOLATED WHILE THE MATERIAL WAS IDENTIFIED AND THE SHIPPER CONTACTED.  SILICASORB WAS USED TO ABSORB ALL SPILLED MATERIAL AND THE DRUMS WERE CLEANED BEFORE FORWARDING.

WHEN THE TRAILER DOOR WAS OPENED FOR UNLOADING, ONE CARTON FELL TO THE DOCK FLOOR.  THE AREA WAS ISOLATED AND CHEMTREC AND THE SHIPPER WERE CONTACTED.  TE SPILL WAS NEUTRALIZED AS INSTRUCTED.  THE DAMAGED CONTAINERS WERE PLACED INSIDE A RECOVERY DRUM ALONG WITH THE NEUTRALIZED MATERIAL.  THE UNDAMAGED CONTAINERS WERE PLACED INSIDE A SEPARATE RECOVERY DRUM AND FORWARDED.  ALL CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE HELD FOR DISPOSITION.

DOCKWORKER NOTICED A DRIP FROM THE SKID CONTAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL AND INVESTIGATED.  AFTER REMOVING THE TOP FREIGHT FROM THE SKID, ONE PUNCTURED CONTAINER WAS FOUND PUSHED AGAINST ADJACENT FREIGHT.  THE DAMAGED CONTAINER WAS PLACED INSIDE A RECOVERY PAIL AND THE SPILLAGE WIPED UP.

THE FREIGHT WAS LOADED IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER NEXT TO TWO VERY LARGE CARTONS.  FROM THE RIDE OF THE TRAILER, CARTONS DAMAGED FROM THE HEAVY FREIGHT.  PRODUCT WAS CLEANED UP WITH FLOOR DRY AND PLACED INTO RECOVERY DRUM.  AWAITING DISPOSITION FROM THE SHIPPER.  TO PREVENT FURTHER ACCIDENTS A CLAIM PREVENTION FORM WAS FILLED OUT TO HELP FUTURE ACCIDENTS FROM OCCURRING.

column168: AN ARKANSAS FREIGHTWAYS ROAD DRIVER REPORTED A THICK LIQUID LEAKING FROM THE REAR OF TRAILER P3039 UPON HIS ARRIVAL AT THE AUS TERMINAL.  THE SHIPMENT WAS DELIVERED TO THE CONSIGNEE FOR THEIR INSPECTION WHERE IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT ONE DRUM HAD A 5" CRACK TO THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER.  THIS WAS APPARENTLY A RECONDITIONED DRUM WITH MANY OF THE MARKINGS UNABLE TO READ.  THE AGE ON THE DRUM COULD HAVE CONTRIBUTED TO IT'S FAILURE AS IT APPEARS TO HAVE RUST AROUND THE CRACK.  THE SEALER WAS COVERED WITH SAWDUST AND THE CONTENTS PLACED IN OUR DUMPSTER.

column168: THE DRUM WAS SITTING ON REAR OF TRAILER, DRUM TRUCK WAS PUSHED UNDER IN ORDER TO PICK UP AND DRUM WAS PUNCTURED ON LEFT SIDE/BOTTOM OF DRUM.  THE DRUM WAS PULLED OFF ONTO THE DOCK AND APPLIED SODIUM BICARBONATE AS INSTRUCTED BY THE SHIPPER.
THE MANWAY COVER GASKET BECAME FRAYED, WORN AND CRACKED.  THIS ALLOWED VAPORS TO ESCAPE BETWEEN THE GASKET AND MANWAY COVER.  SHIPPER FAILED TO PROPERLY SECURE CAR.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: WHEN THE SHIPMENT WAS TENDERED THE SHIPPER WAS ASKED IF IT CONTAINED GASOLINE, HE SAID IT DID NOT.  DURING LOADING IT WAS TIPPED AND ONE TO TWO OUNCES OF GASOLINE SPILLED ON THE BAGGAGE COMPARTMENT FLOOR.  THE BOX WAS IMMEDIATELY REMOVED FROM THE AIRCRAFT AND THE SPILL WAS SOAKED UP WITH RAGS.  THE DANGEROUS GOODS HOTLINE, DOT AND OPBOP WERE NOTIIFED.  NO INJURY PROPERTY OR AIRCRAFT DAMAGE OCCURRED.  FOLLOWING CLEAN-UP THE AIRCRAFT DEPARTED FOR CHICAGO ON TIME.  THE BOX CONTAINED A WOOD CHIPPER, A NEW, ONE-OF-A-KIND PROTOTYPE UNIT, BEING SHIPPED FOR MARKETING AND PROMOTIONAL PURPOSES RATHER THAN USE, ACCORDING TO THE SHUPPER.
DRIVER WAS UNLOADING INTO CUSTOMERS TANK AND IT ALREADY HAD SOME IN IT. OVERFILLED CUSTOMERS TANK.
EXTERNAL PUNCTURE PROBABLY BY DRUM TRUCK.  DAMAGE ON ARRIVAL.  CHERRYVILLE ORIG TERM NOTIFIED.

CAR WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING FROM TOP LOADING BALL COCK VALVE HANDLE DURING INTERCHANGE AND WAS PLACED TO AN ISOLATED TRACK FOR INSPECTION AND REPAIRS.  THE INSPECTION INDICATED THE TOP LOADING BALL COCK VALVE HANDLE WAS BROKEN OFF AND VALVE TURNED 1/4 OPEN.  THE BALL COCK VAVLE WAS CLOSED AND TIGHTENED.  A 3 INCH PLUG/WIRED VALVE CLOSED, REPLACED COVER AND PLACED SEAL.  CAR WAS THEN OKAY TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.  CHEMTEC, BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES AND SHIPPER WERE ALL NOTIFIED AT TIME CAR WAS FOUND LEAKING.

THE SHIPPER RESPONDED BY SENDING A HAZMAT TEAM AND TWO COMPANY REPRESENTATIVES TO INSPECT THE LOAD.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT A TOTE TANK IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER WAS LEAKING AT THE TOP SEAL AREA.  THIS SEAL WAS REPLACED AND ALL SPILLED MATERIAL CLEAN UP.

UPON OPENING THE TRAILER DOORS AT THE RECEIVER, THE DRIVER NOTICED THAT THE VERY LAST DRUM ON THE LOAD HAD LEAKED SOME OF ITS CONTENTS ON THE TRAILER FLOOR.  THIS DRUM HAD APPARENTLY BEEN SEALED WITH AN ALUMINUM BUNG AND THE MATERIAL IN THE DRUM REACTED WITH IT AND IT DECOMPOSED THE ALUMINIUM SEAL.  THE MATERIAL WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH BICARBONATE AND THE TRAILER WAS CRASHED.

SHIPMENT WAS BEING TRANSPORTED TO DEPARTURE RAMP AREA IN CART 9948 FOR FLIGHT 840 TO EWR ETR 1330.  ON ARRIVAL AT A/C RUNENR DISCOVERED ONE PACKAGE MISSING AND BACKTRACKED TO LOCATE IT.  HE FOUND SAME AT AOA ENTRANCE TO CARGO RAMP.  PACKAGE WAS VISIBLY CRUSHED SO HE NOTIFIED CARGO SERVICE SUPV. BY RADIO.  HE THEN ASSISTED THE SUPERVISOR IN SECURING THE AREA AND DIVERTING TRAFFIC AROUND THE AFFECTED AREA.  AN ILL. DEPT. OF NUCLEAR SAFETY REP. SUPERVISED THE CLEANUP AND RECOVERY DONE BY MEDI-PHYSICS TEAM AND CHICAGO FIRE DEPT.  SUSPENT PACKAGE DAMAGED BY PASSING GRAVEL TRUCK AFTER FALLING FROM CARGO CART.  DEBRIS PICKED UP BY SHIPPER.

column168: UPON UNLOADING CARTONS AT DESTINATION TERMINAL FREIGHT HAD FALLEN FROM INPROPER LOADING.

IT APPEARS THAT THE BOX WAS PUNCTURED DURING TRANSIT TO OUR SERVICE CENTER.  THERE WAS A SHIFTING OF FREIGHT IN THE TRAILER DURING THE MOVING OF SAID TRAILER.  THE ORIGIN SERVICE CENTER HAD BEEN NOTIFIED ABOUT THE PROBLEM IN LOADING.  THEY WILL COUNSEL THE EMPLOYEE ON THE CORRECT MANNER FREIGHT OF THIS KIND IS TO BE LOADED.  THE MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED IN A SMALL RECOVERY DRUM ALONG WITH ALL CLEANING MATERIAL USED.  WILL BE DISPOSED OF THROUGH PROPER CHANNELS

SAFETY KLEEN PERSONNEL WAS FILLING STORAGE TANK FOR PERCHLOROETHYLENE, IN A CUSTOMERS DRY CLEANING PLANT.  TANK OVERFLLED WITH PERCHLOROETHYLENE.  THE REPRESENTATIVE OS SAFETY-KLEEN WAS WATCHING FILLING PROCESS WHEN OVERFILL OCURRED.  THE AUTOMATIC SHUT OFF ON FILL NOZZLE FAILED TO KICK OFF WHEN STORAGE TANK WAS FULL CAUSING AN OVERFILL.  THE TANK GAUGE ON CUSTOMERS TANK DID NOT OPERATE.  THE FLOW OF SOLVENT WAS STOPPED IMMEDIATELY CUSTOMER PROVIDED A LARGE COMFORTER TO ABSORB THE PERCHLOROETHYLENE.  PERC WAS WIPED UP WITH COMFORTER AND COMFORTER WAS PLACED INTO DRY CLEAING MACHINE AND RECOVERD BACK INTO CLEANING SYSTEM.  SOME RESIDUAL PERCHLOROEHTYLENE WAS ABSORBED WIHT CHEMICAL ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND PLACED INTO DRUMS WITH WASTE FILTERS.

column168: WHILE TIPPING DRUM IN PREPARATION FOR UNLOADING FROM TRUCK, DRIVER NOTICED A SMALL AMOUNT OF ACID TRICKLING FROM A CRACK IN THE SIDE OF THE TOP OF THE DRUM.  THE DRIVER RETURNED THE LEAKING DRUM TO THE UPRIGHT POSITION, IN WHICH IT WAS NOT LEAKING, AND OFFLOADED THE REMAINING DRUMS IN THE CUSTOMER'S SHIPMENT.  THE DRIVER THEN SECURED THE DEFECTIVE DRUM IN THE TRUCK, SPREAD SODA ASH AROUND THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM TO ABSORB AND NEUTRALIZE ANY ACID THAT MIGHT ESCAPE FROM THE CRACK DUE TO JOSTLING DURING TRANSPORTATION. IT IS NOT KNOWN WHAT CAUSED THE PACKAGING FAILURE.  THE SUPERVISOR SUGGESTED TWO POSSIBLE CAUSES: PACKAGE FAILURE DUE TO AGE, OR PACKAGE FAILURE DUE TO IMPROPER BANDING.  (DRUMS ON PALLETS ARE BANDED TOGETHER FOR STABILITY.  IF THE DRUMS, REPEATEDLY, WERE BANDED TO TIGHTLY TO ALLOW FOR PRODUCT EXPANSION DUE TO TEMPERATURE CHANGES, INTERNAL PRESSURE MAY HAVE WEAKENED THE SEAMS). RECOMMENDATIONS TO IMPROVE HANDLING: 1) REMOVE OLDER DRUMS FROM SERVICE, 2) INSTRUCT: A) DRUM FILLERS TO CHECK MORE CAREFULLY FOR PACKAGE INTEGRITY BEFORE FILLING, B) LOADER AND DRIVER TO CHECK CAREFULLY FOR PACKAGE INTEGRITY BEFORE LOADING, C) DRUM BANDER TO ALLOW FOR EXPANSION WHEN BANDING PALLETIZED DRUMS.

column168: THIS SHIPMENT ARRIVED AT OUR FRESNO CA. SERVICE CENTER ON JULY 23, 1991 FROM OUR LONG BEACH SERVICE CENTER. IT TURNED OUT TO BE ORGANOPHOSPHORUS PESTICIDE LIQUID N.O.S. 95% ESTHLSSDISECBUTY POISON B UN-3018.  WE CHECKED EMERGENCY RESPONSE GUIDE BOOK AND CALLED MC SO THAT THEY COULD SENT US MSDS PAPERS, SO THAT WE WOULD TAKE THE PROPER STEPS TO AVOID EXPOSURE TO ANY EMPLOYEES.  WE SPREAD ABSORBENT MATERIAL ON LIQUID.  THERE WAS ABOUT 1 QUART OF LIQUID SPILLED ON THE FLOOR.  FMC NEUTRALIZED THS SPILLED LIQUID. 2 WOOD STRIPS IN TRAILER FLOOR WERE REMOVED AND FMC WILL DISPOSE OF IT. MSDS SHEETS WERE REVIEWED WITH THE EMPLOYEES THAT WERE NEAR OR HAD CONTACT WITH LIQUID.  NONE OF THE EMPLOYEES REPORTED ANY SYMPTONS OF ANY KIND. THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM ALONG SEAM LOOKED TO BE WHERE THE LIWUID WAS LEAKING FROM.  THE SPILL COULD NOT HAVE BENN PREVENTED BY OUR COMPANY BECAUSE THE SPILL RESULTED IN A BAD DRUM WHEATER DUE TO WORKMANSHIP OR DEFECT IN METAL.

column168: PACKAGE WAS FOUND BY UNLOADER.  VERY STRONG VAPORS PRESENT, SO THE TRAILER WAS EVACUATED.  ONCE THE PACKAGE WAS REMOVED, THE TRAILER WAS PULLED OFF THE DOCK AND ISOLATED TO VENT THE VAPORS.  CAUSE OF SPILLAGE: THE BOTTLE'S CAP HAD A SMALL HOLE (ASSUMED TO VENT).  WHEN THE BOTTLE IS INVERTED, THE CONTENTS LEAK OUT; HENCE THE REASON THE BOTTLES ARE ENCLOSED IN A PLASTIC BAG.  THIS METHOD OF PACKAGING IS INHERENTLY DANGEROUS DUE TO THE FACT THAT 1) THE SEAM ON THE BAG IS INADEQUATE AS WELL AS THE THICKNESS AT THE BAG ITSELF; 2) ONCE THE CONTENTS LEAK OUT, THEY FORM BLADDERS THAT PRESS AGAINST EACH OTHER (AS WELL AS OTHER BOTTLES).  THIS, THEY BURST EASILY WHEN JARRED.

column168: ON TUESDAY, JULY 23, 1991, AT APPROXIMATELY 0930 HOURS, THE CREW OF TRAIN CSXT HOPEWELL TURN REPORTED TO THE YARDMASTER THAT TANK CAR GATX 44977, WHICH WAS IN THEIR TRAIN SITTING ON NO. 4 TRACK IN THE NORTH YARD AT ACCA YARD, WAS LEAKING FROM AROUND THE FITTINGS ON TOP OF THE TANK CAR. RF&P ASSISTANT ENGINEER J.R. HALL WAS NOTIFIED AND MADE AN INSPECTION OF THE TANK CAR AT 1000 HOURS.  THE INSPECTION REVEALED THE CONTENTS OF THE TANK CAR HAD BEEN SEEPING FROM THE FITTING CONTAINING THE SAFETY PRESSURE RELIEF DISC.  NO PONDING OR GROUND ACCUMULATION WAS EVIDENT.  APPARENTLY THE SLIGHT SEEPAGE ONLY OCCURRED WHILE THE CAR WAS IN MOTION. THE TANK CAR WAS REMOVED FROM THE TRAIN AND ISOLATED IN THE EAST YARD (PIGGYBACK RAMP TRACK) UNTIL REPAIRS COULD BE MADE. CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED AT 1010 HOURS AND THEY, IN TURN, NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER S.T. SERVICES, INCORPORATED, 1800 FRANKFURST AVENUE, BALTIMORE (FAIRFIELD) MARYLAND 21226. DON HAHN OF S.T. SERVICES, INCORPORATED, CALLED AT 1030 HOURS AND ADVISED HE WOULD CONTACT GENERAL RAILWAY SERVICES OF SUFFOLK, VIRGINIA, TO RESPOND AND MAKE REPAIRS TO THE TANK CAR. REPRESENTATIVES OF GENERAL RAILWAY SERVICES ARRIVED AT ACCA YARD AND IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK WAS A RUPTURED SAFETY PRESSURE RELIEF DISC.  THE DISC WAS REPLACED AND REPAIRS WERE COMPLETED TO THE TANK CAR AT 1500 HOURS.  THE TANK CAR WAS RELEASED TO GO BACK INTO NORMAL RAIL SERVICE AT THAT TIME.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING THIS SHIPMENT THE DRIVER DROPPED THE 5 GALLON PAIL CAUSING THE CLOSURE TO OPEN AND THE CONTENTS OF THE PAIL TO SPILL. PRODUCT TRANSFER HOSE WAS CONNECTED TO RECEIVING STORAGE TANK, TRANSFER OPERTATION BEGAN, STORAGE TANK VALVE ASSEMBLY BEGAN TO LEAK, OPERATOR PUT TRANSFER INTO REVERSE SO TO STOP THE FLOW OF PRODUCT, AIR WAS SUCKED INTO ISO TANK AND CAUSED PRODUCT TO START TO FOAM UP.  THIS FOAMING ACTION CAUSED THE PRODUCT TO EXPAND, THE OPERATED NOTICED THAT MATERIAL BEGAN TO FOAM OUT OF THE TOP HATCH ON THE ISO CONTAINER.  THE TRANSFER OPERATION WAS STOPPED AND SPILLED PRODUCT WAS CLEANED UP IMMEDIATELY.  APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  FURTHER KNOWLEDGE OF THE PRODUCT WAS REALIZED, ALL PERSONNEL HAVE BEEN BRIEFED THAT AIR MIXED WITH THIS PRODUCT SHALL CAUSE MATERIAL TO FOAM.

DRIVER WAS GOING TO MOVE BOX WITH HANDTRUCK AND SLID HIS HANTRUCK UNDER BOX BUT CAUGHT THE CORNER OF THE BOX AND BROKE A 1 GALLON GLASS BOTTLE OF XYLENE, FLAMMABLE LIQUID, UN-1307.  WE CALLED SHIPPER TO HAVE THEM SEND US MSDS FORMS.  THEN WE CHECK EMERGENCY RESPONSE GUIDE BOOK TO SEE WHAT ACTION WAS BEST TO TAKE.  WE PUT ABSORBENT ON LIQUID TO CONTROL AND ABSORB LIQUID. EMPLOYEE WAS SAT DOWN AND MSDS SHEETS WERE REVIEWED WITH HIM.  HE SAID THAT HE HAD NO SYMPTOMS AND FELT FINE.  ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS COLLECTED AND DISPOSED OF BY LEGAL REQUIREMENTS.  DRIVER WAS INSTRUCTED TO BE CAREFULL WHEN USING HANDTRUCK OR OTHER METHODS OF MOVING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  THIS IS STANDARD TRAINING PROCEDURE FOR ALL EMPLOYEES.

AT APPROXIMATELY 0052 HOURS, SATURDAY, JULY 6, 1991, EMPLOYEES AT THE ELHKART, INDIANA CONRAIL RAIL YARD OBSERVED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OF TANK CAR GATX-75486 DURING ARRIVAL INSPECTION OF CONRAIL TRAIN OIEL-4 ON TRACK 4 RECEIVING.  TANK CAR WAS LOCATED THIRTY-FOR CARS FORM THE HEAD END OF THE TRAIN AND LEAKING APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON PRODUCT EVERY MINUTE.  CAR WAS ISOLATED TO DESIGNATED ISOLATION TRACK AT THE EAST END OF THE RECEIVING YARD.  CHEMTREC, SHIPPER, AAR/BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES AS WELL AS THE ELKHART FIRE DEPARTMENT WERE NOTIFIED.  CONRAIL MAINTENANCE OF WAY PERSONNEL CONSTRUCTED A DIKE AROUND THE TANK CAR TO CONTAIN PRODUCT WHICH HAD INCREASED TO A LOSS RATE OF FIVE GALLONS PER MINUTE.  INSPECTION OF TANK CAR AT APPROXIMATELY 05400 HOURS BY AAR/BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES INSPECTOR T. DAVIS INDICATED THAT THE CARS INTERIOR LINING HAD FAILED AND PRODUCT HAD CORRODED THROUGH TANK CAR SHELL NEAR THE MIDDLE OF THE CAR ALONG THE CENTER SILL.

AT APPROXIMATELY 1215 HOURS, WEDNESDAY, JULY 10, 1991, TWO CONRAIL EMPLOYEES AT THE CONRAIL, DICKINSON, WV RAIL YARD WERE SPLASHED BY PRODUCT COMING FROM THE MANWAY AREA OF TANK CAR MCPX-21050 WHILE CAR WAS BEING SWITCHED AT THE SOUTH END OF THE YARD.  CAR WAS ISOLATED AND CHEMTREC AND THE SHIPPER WERE NOTIFIED.  RESPONSE PERSONNEL FROM UNION CARBIDE (CONSIGNEE) ARRIVED TO THE LOCATION OF THE CAR AND UPON INSPECTION FOUND THAT THE MANWAY COVER BOLTS WERE LOOSE ALLOWING PRODUCT TO ESCAPE FROM THE CAR.  MANWAY BOLTS WERE SECURED AND CAR WAS CLEARED TO DESTINATION AT 1530 HOURS, JULY 10, 1991.  THE TWO CONRAIL EMPLOYEES SPLASHED BY THE PRODUCT, MR. W. STEELE AND MR. R. ROMAINE DID NOT REQUIRE OR RECEIVE ANY MEDICAL ATTENTION.

AT APPROXIMATELY 2:00 PM ON JULY 10, 1991 TWO ENVIRITE DRIVERS WERE LOADING MATERIAL FROM A GREGORY GALVANIZING STORAGE TANK INTO ENVIRITE TANKER 8410.  UPON COMPLETION OF LOADING APPROXIMATELY 2 QUARTS OF MATERIAL REMAINED IN THE HOSE USED TO TRANSFER THE MATERIAL.  AS THE DRIVERS WERE DISCONNECTING THE HOSE THE MATERIAL STILL IN THE HOSE SPILLED OUT ONTO THE ASPHALT AREA WHERE LOADING HAD BEEN TAKING PLACE.  THE DRIVERS THEN USED ABSORBENT MATERIAL FROM THEIR TANKER SPILL KIT TO ABSORB THE SPILLED MATERIAL. AT 2:30 PM THE DRIVERS CONTACTED THEIR SUPERVISOR AT ENVIRITE CONCERNING THE INCIDENT.  THEY WERE INSTRUCTED TO INFORM THE GREGORY GALVANIZING REPRESENTATIVE OF THE TANKER.  THE DRIVERS THEN RETURNED TO ENVIRITE WITH OUT INCIDENT. TO INSURE THE INCIDENT DOES NOT HAPPEN AGAIN DRIVERS WILL BE INSTRUCTED TO INSURE THAT HOSES USED FOR LOADING ARE PROPERLY VACUUMED OUT OR DRAINED INTO PERMITTED STORAGE AREAS PRIOR TO DISASSEMBLY.

A CRACK WAS NOTICED ON THE VAPOR VENT LINE WHEN THE DRIVERS WERE DELIVERING AT THE CUSTOMER.  A SMALL AMOUNT OF VAPOR, WHICH IS NONTOXIC, WAS EXITING THIS CRACK.  THIS SMALL VAPOR LOSS PRESENTED ONLY MINOR PROBLEMS FOR THE DRIVERS, HENCE THE DELIVERY WAS SAFELY CARRIED OUT AND THE TRAILER WAS EMPTIED.  AFTER THE DELIVERY WAS COMPLETED, THE DRIVERS REDUCED THE INNER VESSEL PRESSURE AND RETURNED TO THEIR TERMINAL WITHOUT INCIDENT.  ON RETURN TO REIDSVILLE, NORTH CAROLINA, THE TRAILER WAS TRANSFERRED TO AIR PRODUCTS' AREA MAINTENANCE FACILITY IN DELAWARE CITY, DELAWARE, WHERE IT WAS PLACED OUT OF SERVICE.  REPAIRS WERE CARRIED OUT AND THE UNIT RETURNED TO SERVICE.

FIVE REJECTED PALLETS WERE ON A TRAILER WAITING TO BE RETURNED TO RINECO. ONE PALLET BEGAN TO SMOKE, IT WAS PROMPTLY REMOVED AND PLACED IN THE TESTING AREA.  JOHN WHITNEY WAS CONTACTED AS DIRECTED BY THE MANIFEST. RINECO INDICATED THAT THE LOAD WAS POSSIBLY HIGH IN THC AND THE PARTICLES WERE ATTEMPTING TO SOLIDIFY CREATING HEAT AND CAUSING LIDS TO BLOW OFF THE PAILS.  THE SMOKING PALLET WAS ISOLATED AND ALLOWED TO COOL.  THE PAILS WERE COOLED AND PLACED IN OVERPACKS FOR RETURN TO RINECO.  A SMALL QUANTITY (APPROX TWO LBS) WAS SPILLED WHEN THE LIDS BLEW OFF.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP AS DIRECTED.

column168: ON JULY 23, 1991, LAIDLAW ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (TS), INC., LAUREL, MD LOADED A SHIPMENT OF HAZARDOUS WASTE MATERIAL TO BE SHIPPED TO A PROCESSING PLANT IN MORGAN CITY, LA.  THIS MATERIAL WAS BEING TRANSPORTED BY THE TRANSPORTATION DIVISION OF LAIDLAW ENVIRONMENTAL: LAIDLAW ENVIRONMENTAL (TG), INC. OF PINEWOOD, SC. THE SHIPMENT CONSISTED OF 135 CONTAINERS OF 55 GALLONS OR SMALLER.  SOME OF THE CONTAINERS WERE OVERPACKED IN LARGER DRUMS.  THIS WAS A MIXED SHIPMENT CONTAINING SEVENTEEN (17) DIFFERENT WASTE STREAMS OF WHICH ELEVEN (11) WERE DOT-HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  THE OTHER SIX (6) WASTE STREAMS WERE NON-REGULATED.  THE CHARACTERISTICS OF THE MATERIALS INCLUDE: COMBUSTIBLE LIQUIDS, ORM-E'S, FLAMMABLE SOLIDS AND FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS.  THE COMBUSTIBLE LIQUID INCLUDES ROOFING PAINT CONTAINING AN ALUMINUM PIGMENTS, AND KEROSENE TANK BOTTOMS.  THE FLAMMABLE SOLID CONSISTED OF A DISPERSANT MIXTURE SIMILAR IN COMPOSITION TO A HIGHWAY FLARE.  THE FLAMMABLE LIQUID CONSISTED OF PAINT AND THE ORM-E'S CONSISTED PRIMARILY OF TRASH AND DEBRIS CONTAINING LOW LEVELS OF EPA REGULATED MATERIAL INCLUDING TRASH CONTAMINATED WITH A LOW CONCENTRATION OF LINDANE FROM THE MANUFACTURE OF PET SHAMPOO. THE EXACT MAKE-UP OF THE SHIPMENT FOLLOWS: 2-55 GALLON STEEL DRUMS OF KEROSENE TANK BOTTOMS, 5-5 GALLON PLASTIC CONTAINERS OF ALUMINUM ROOF PAINT, 8-5 GALLON PLASTIC CONTAINERS OF ALUMINUM ROOF PAINT OVERPACKED IN 20 GALLON FIBER DRUMS, 1-55 GALLON STEEL DRUM OF DRIED PAINT CHIPS AND DEBRIS CONTAINING LEAD, 45-5 GALLON PLASTIC CONTAINER OF CS/CN-PYROMIX, A MIXTURE OF POTASSIUM CHLORATE, SUGAR, TRASH, ALUMINUM PARTS, FLOOR SWEEPING COMPOUND, AND TEAR GAS GRENADES, THIS IS FROM THE MANUFACTURE OF THE DISPERSANT PART, AND DOES NOT CONTAIN THE BOOSTERS OR PRIMERS, 2-55 GALLON STEEL DRUMS OF FURNACE SALTS CONTAINING BARIUM CHLORIDE, 3-55 GALLON STEEL DRUMS OF TRASH CONTAMINATED WITH LINDANE, 3-30 GALLON FIBER DRUMS OF TRASH CONTAMINATED WITH SMALL AMOUNTS OF EPA-REGULATED MATERIAL (PROTECTIVE CLOTHING, ETC.), 16-55 GALLON STEEL DRUMS OF TRASH CONTAMINATED WITH SMALL AMOUNTS OF EPA-REGULATED MATERIAL (PROTECTIVE CLOTHING, ETC.), 15-55 GALLON STEEL DRUMS OF TRASH CONTAMINATED WITH PAINTS AND RESINS CONTAINING LEAD, 1-55 GALLON PLASTIC DRUM OF POLYMER INTERMEDIATE-TRIALLYCYANURATE-CONTAINING, ETHYLENE CHLORIDE AS A SOLVENT, 11-55 GALLON STEEL DRUMS CONTAINING FLAMMABLE PAINT, 8-55 GALLON STEEL DRUMS CONTAINING COMBUSTIBLE PAINT, 17-55 GALLON STEEL DRUMS OF NON-HAZARDOUS WASTE (POLYMERS, EMPTY CANS, ETC.). THESE MATERIALS WERE LOADED IN LAUREL, MD BETWEEN 9:00 AM AND 10:30 AM. THE FLAMMABLE SOLID MATERIAL WAS LOADED ON THE RIGHT REAR OF THE TRAILER. THE TRUCK LEFT LAUREL AT 10:30 AM HEADED SOUTH.  AT APPROXIMATELY 12:15 PM, WE WERE NOTIFIED THAT THE VEHICLE, ON I-95 SOUTHBOUND NEAR LOTTON, VA WAS ON FIRE. column168: SHIPMENT ARRIVED AT CON-WAY WESTERN EXPRESS, STOCKTON, CA ON 76-31-91 FROM LOS ANGELES, CA.  EMPLOYEES OPENED TRAILER DOOR AND PROCEEDED TO UNLOAD FREIGHT OUT OF TRAILER.  THEY PULLED OUT A PALLET AND PLACED IT ON THE DOCK.  AN EMPLOYEE NOTICED THAT THE PLASTIC COVERING THE CANS WERE SLIGHTLY DAMP.  EMPLOYEE NOTIFIED SUPERVISOR.  WE CALLED SHIPPER FOR MSDS SHEETS AND ALSO CHECKED EMERGENCY RESPONSE GUIDE BOOK.  AFTER READING MSDS SHEETS AND SPEAKING WITH SHIPPER WE FOUND 2 5 GALLON PAILS THAT HAD A HOLE IN THEM.  THE PAINT THAT COVERED UP THE HOLES HAD BUBBLED UP AND THIS LET THE LIQUID RUN OUT.  THE HOLES WERE ABOUT 2 INCHES FROM TOP OF 5 GALLON PAILS.  THE 2 LEAKING PAILS WERE THEN PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM AND MARKED AND SENT ON TO CONSIGNEE.  MSDS SHEETS WERE AGAIN REVIEWED WITH EMPLOYEE. EMPLOYEED STATED HE HAD NO SYMPTONS AND HE FELT FINE.  WE FEEL THAT THIS MATERIAL ESCAPED DUE TO POOR MANUFACTURING OF PAILS (DEFECT IN 5 GALLON PAILS).  WE COULD NOT HAVE PREVENTED THIS SPILL.

column42: HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCE, LIQUID OR SOLID, N.O.S. OR ORM-E, LIQUID OR SOLID, N.O.S.
column168: CWMU 7032 WAS BEING PICKED UP BY CONSIGNEE REPRESENTATIVE AT CARRIER'S INTERMODAL FACILITY.  A ROLL-OFF TYPE TRUCK WAS BEING USED TO TRANSPORT CONTAINER AND WHEN THE CONTAINER WAS TILTED TO ABOUT A 30 DEGREE ANGLE DURING LOADNG THE DRIVER NOTED LIQUID LEAKING FROM THE REAR OF CONTAINER. LOADING WAS STOPPED AT THAT POINT, ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS PLACED BEHIND CONTAINER TO CATCH RUN-OFF.  CONSIGNEE WAS NOTIFIED. A METAL DRUM WAS USED TO CATCH LEAKAGE IN ADDITION TO ABSORBENT MATERIAL. CONTENTS OF TRAILER WAS WOODEN FLOORING WHICH HAD AT SOME TIME BEEN IN CONTACT WITH TRANSFORMERS CONTAINING PCB'S, THEREFORE, PRODUCT WAS BEING HANDLED AS HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCE AND WAS ENROUTE TO BE DISPOSED OF.  LIQUID WAS APPARENTLY WATER WHICH HAD GOTTEN INTO THE CONTAINER DURING LOADING AND WHICH HAD LEACHED FROM THE WOOD WHICH HAD BEEN EXPOSED TO WATER. CONSIGNEE RESPONDED TO SCENE AND REMOVED ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIAL. CONTAINER WAS MOVED TO CONSIGNEE FACILITY WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

THEY NOTIFIED COUNTY HEALTH, STATE HEALTH & EPA HAZMAT CONTRACTOR WAS CONTACTED FOR CLEAN UP. COSTS ARE UNKNOWN AT THIS TIME.  STORM DRAIN WAS FLUSHED AND VACUUMED FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.

column168: CORSAN DRIVER IN TRACTOR 512, PULLING TRAILER 228007, HAD ARRIVED AT LAID LAW ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (TES), INC., STORAGE FACILITY WITH A LOAD OF DRUMS.  AS PART OF NORMAL PROCEDURE THE REAR DOORS OF THE TRAILER MUST BE OPENED PRIOR TO FINAL POSITIONING AT UNLOADING DOCK.  WHEN THE DRIVER OPENED THE REAR DOOR, ONE 45 GALLON DRUM FELL FROM THE TRUCK ONTO HARD SURFACED AREA.  THE FORCE OF THE FALL CAUSED THE LID TO SEPARATE FROM THE DRUM.  THE CONTENTS SPILLED ONTO HARD SURFACED AREA.  THE FROCE OF THE FALL CAUSED THE LID TO SEPARATE FROM THE DRUM.  THE CONTENTS SPILLED ONTO YARD SURFACED AREA.  THE WASTE PROFILE SHEET INDICATED TRACE AMOUTNS OF BENZENE.  THE LAIDLAW ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (TES) FACILITY PERSONNEL INITIATED IMMEDITE CLEAN-UP USING ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  THE CONTAMINATED MATERIAL WAS PLACED IN STEEL DRUMS FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.  THE CONTAMINATED HARD SURFACE WAS WASHED WITHOUT SOLVENT AND RINSATE COLLECTED FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.  THERE WAS NO FUGITIVE EMMISSIONS AND PROFUCT SPILLAGE WAS CONFINED TO THE HARD SURFACED AREA.  THE TYPE OF DRUMS, AND LOADING AND BRACING PROCEDURE ARE BEING INVESTIGATED, AND APPROPRIATE CHANGED WILL BE MADE TO PREVENT A SIMILAR INCIDENT.

column168: ADVISED BY ROUGEMERE YD. PERSONNEL THAT THE YARD CREW SWITCHING CAR ETCX 21021 OBSERVERED A SLIGHT VAPOR RELEASE FROM THE MANWAY COVER AREA WHILE MOVING THE CAR INTO #25 TRACK.  RESPONDED TO THE YARD & INSPECTED CAR FOUND A SLIGHT ODOR AND NO SPILLAGE ON THE CAR SIDES.  INSPECTED TOP FITTINGS AND FOUND 4 OF 6 MANWAY COVER BOLTS HAD NOT BEEN SECURED.  TWO (2) OF THE FOUR (4) BOLTS ONLY HAND TIGHT.  TIGHTENED BOLTS AND HAD YARD CREW MOVE & "SHAKE" CAR.  NO SPILLAGE OR LEAKAGE NOTED.  CAR RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT AND SHIPPER ADVISED OF CONDITION OF CAR.

ADVISED BY YARDMASTER FULLER THAT MECHANICAL DEPT EMPLOYEES WORKING AROUND CAR PROX 40414 IN TRACK C09 PORT HURON YD. NOTED A SLIGHT ODOR AROUND CAR. AREA WAS CHECKED WITH "GASTRAC" METER AND NO VAPORS WERE NOTED ON THE GROUND.  HOWEVER, TOP OF CAR WAS CHECKED AND DETECTABLE LIMIT WERE NOTED. SHIPPER ADVISED AND DOW E/R TEAM ARRIVED AT YARD 1520 HRS AND SECURED CAR AT 1545 HRS. BY REPLACING VACCUM RELIEF DEVICE SPRING.

UPON BREAKING OUT THE TRAILER, DRIVER HOLZER FOUND 1 CRUSHED STEEL 5 GALLON CAN DAMAGED FROM THE TOP.  THIS RESULTED FROM THE ORIGIN TERMINAL - FRESNO - LOADING IMPROPERLY.  ORIGIN TERMINAL, FRESNO NEEDS TO LOAD AND SECURE FREIGHT PROPER TO DEST BREAK-OUT.

OUR UNIT UNLOADING SODIUM HYDROXIDE IN CUSTOMER PLANT, HOSE FAILED APPROXIMATELY 12" FROM POINT OF ATTACHMENT TO TOP UNLOAD POINT ON TANK RESULTING IN LOSS OF APPROXIMATELY 50 GALS OF MATERIAL.  MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED AND THEN NEUTRALIZED.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES.  PROPERTY DAMAGE WAS LIMITED TO PAINT REMOVAL FROM STORAGE TANK AND SHED NEXT TO TANK.  TO PREVENT FUTURE REOCCURRANCES WE ARE GOING TO USE A SOLID PIPE FROM THE TOP OF THE TRAILER DOWN TO FENDER HEIGHT TO AVOID THE SEVERE BENDING OF THE UNLOADING HOSE WHEN IT IS ATTACHED.
CUSTOMER ORDERED TOO MUCH PRODUCT.  WHILE DISCONNECTING HOSE, SIPHON ACTION CAUSED PRODUCT TO COME OUT OF TANK AND SPILL.

column168: OUR VEHICLE, TRAVELING SOUTH ON 2ND STREET, MADE AN ABRUPT STOP TO AVOID HITTING A CAR RUNNING A RED LIGHT ON DOUGLAS AVE.  OUR DRIVER PULLED ONTO A SIDE STREET (DOUGLAS AVE.) TO CHECK HIS LOAD.  HE DISCOVERED THREE (3) DRUMS HAD TIPPED OVER AND PRODUCT (HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTION) WAS LEAKING. FROM THE TRUCK TRAILER.  THE AUTHORITIES WERE CONTACTED AND THE DES MOINES HAZMAT UNIT, FIRE DEPT.  AND POLICE DEPT.  RESPONDED.  THE DRUMS WERE RIGHTED, SECURED AND THE SPILLED LIQUID WAS FLUSHED WITH WATER.  SAND WAS USED TO DIKE THE SPILLED LIQUID FROM ENTERING THE SEWERS.  UPON RETURNING THE VEHICLE TO OUR PLANT, THE DRUMS WERE LATER WEIGHED AND IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ONLY ONE DRUM HAD LOST A TOTAL OF 79 POUNDS OR 8.2 GALS. OF HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTION.  (THIS IS CONTRARY TO THE INFORMATION PROVIDED IN THE INITIAL REPORT THAT ESTIMATED THE LOSS AT 30-40 GALS. AND POSSIBLY INDICATED LEAKAGE FROM ALL THREE DRUMS.)  THE TRAILER WHICH HAD BEEN FLUSHED WITH WATER AT THE SCENE WAS AIR DRYED OVERNIGHT AT OUR PLANT.

AS TRAIN 131-17 WAS GOING THROUGH CHEROKEE, KANSAS, THE TRAIN'S CREW DISCOVERED THAT TANK CAR PLMX 9225, LOADED WITH ANHYDROUS AMMONIA, WAS LEAKING.  WHEN THIS WAS REPORTED TO THE TRAIN DISPATCHER, THE DISPATCHER INSTRUCTED THE CREW TO STOP THE TRAIN BEFORE ENTERING THE NEXT TOWN.  THE TRAIN WAS HELD JUST SOUTH OF BEULAH, KANSAS, AWAITING THE ARRIVAL OF A BURLINGTON NORTHERN RAILROAD HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RESPONDER.  THE ANHYDROUS AMMONIA WAS LEAKING FROM THE GAUGING DEVICE DUE TO AN INCOMPLETELY CLOSED GAUGING DEVICE VALVE, AN INCOMPLETELY TIGHTENED GAUGING DEVICE VALVE PLUG, AND AN INCOMPLETELY TIGHTENED PACKING GLANG NUT.  THESE FITTINGS WERE SECURED AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT TO DESTINATION.

column17: P B & S CHEMICAL CO INC

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Piping or Fittings; Vapor Valve
column168: TANKER 15901 WAS PRELOADED WITH SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE FOR SHIPMENT TO REGULAR CUSTOMER ON JUNE 28.  THIS CUSTOMER CALLED CANCELLING SHIPMENT TIL FURTHER NOTICE.  ANOTHER CUSTOMER CALLED REQUESTING SHIPMENT OF THIS PRODUCT.  AT APPROXIMATELY 0800 HOURS OUR DRIVER, RICHARD MCDONALD, WAS ENROUTE TO OUR NITRO PLANT WITH THIS LOAD OF BLEACH TRAVELING EASTBOUND ON RT. 60 FOR WEIGHING UNIT BEFORE TAKING TO CUSTOMER.  WHEN DRIVER STOPPED FOR STOP LIGHT HE NOTICED LIQUID COMING OUT RUPTURE DISK TUBE ON SIDE OF TANKER, CAUSED BY RUPTURE DISK FAILURE.  ONE LANE WAS BLOCKED OFF BY ST. ALBANS FIRE DEPARTMENT WHILE CITY OF ST. ALBANS STREET MAINTENANCE SPREAD SAND OVER SPILLED PRODUCT.  THE SAND WAS PICKED UP BY A STREET SWEEPER AND TRANSPORTED TO OUR FACILITY IN ST. ALBANS.  THE SAND WAS UNLOADED AT OUR FACILITY FOR NEUTRALIZATION IN OUR WASTE TREATMENT FACILITY.  THE STREET SWEEPER EQUIPMENT WAS DECONTAMINATED AT OUR FACILITY WITH WASH WATER GOING INTO OUR WASTE TREATMENT FACILITY.  THE RUPTURE DISK WHICH RUPTURED WAS RATED AT 45 PSI.  THE DISK RUPTURED DUE TO PRESSURE BUILDUP FROM PRODUCT WHICH WAS SEALED IN TANKER FOR THREE "HOT" DAYS PRIOR TO BEING TRANSPORTED.  DURING THIS TIME THIS AREA WAS HAVING TEMPERATURES IN THE HIGH 90'S.  TO PREVENT ANY FURTHER RUPTURE DISK FAILURES OF THIS TYPE WE ARE CURRENTLY USING RUPTURE DISKS WITH A RATED 52 PSI AND THE TANKER WILL BE RELIEVED OF ANY INTERNAL PRESSURE BUILDUP BEFORE DEPARTING OUR FACILITY.

CARMEN REPORTED LEAKING TANK CAR DURING INITIAL TERMINAL AIR BRAKE TEST OF TRAIN 01-142-02.  CAR WAS SET OUT BY TRAIN CREW.  BURLINGTON NORTHERN HAZARDOUS MATERIAL TEAM RESPONDED AND FOUND FITTING BROKEN ON A LIQUID LINE.  SHIPPER CONTRACTED REPAIRS.  REPAIRS WERE MADE AND CAR FORWARDED TO DESTINATION.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing; Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Over-pressurized
column168: THE PALLETIZED DRUMS OF PRODUCT WERE NOT SHRINK WRAPPED TO AVOID MOVEMENT. ONE SKID OF DRUMS HAD A BROKEN SLAT AND ALLOWED A 16 - GAL. DRUM TO FALL OVER AND CONTENTS TO LEAK OUT.  THE DRUMS DID NOT HAVE THE RINGS ON TOP SECURED THUS ALLOWING 2 ADDITIONAL DRUMS TO LEAK SLIGHTLY FROM THE TOPS. THE PRODUCT EVAPORATED AS IT LEAKED SO NO PRODUCT WAS SPILLED OUTSIDE THE TRAILER.  ALL DRUMS SHOULD HAVE THE RINGS SECURED AND THE DRUMS SHOULD BE SHRINK-WRAPPED ON PALLETS TO PREVENT SHIFTING.

column25: DU PONT E I DE NEMOURS & CO
column168: A RAILCAR WAS INVOLVED IN A DERAILMENT AND ROLLED OVER ON ITS SIDE. PRODUCT WAS FOUND LEAKING FROM THE FLANGE OF THE LIQUID LINE MOUNTING PLATE AND SLIGHTLY FROM THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE.  THE LEAKAGE AT THE LIQUID LINE WAS SLOWED BY TIGHTENING THE FLANGE BOLTS AND WITH WEDGES.  A CONTAINER WAS PLACED UNDER TANK UNTIL CAR COULD BE UPRIGHTD. (APPROXIMATELY 65 GALLONS WAS COLLECTED). LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONDERS AS WELL AS CHEMTREC, FRA, NTSB, NRC, PA-DER & THE EPA WERE NOTIFIED IMMEDIATELY AFTER THE INCIDENT OCCURRED. ENVIRONMENTAL AND WRECKING CONTRACTORS WERE CALLED TO THE SCENE. WHEN THE CAR WAS UPRIGHTED, THE REMAINING MATERIAL WAS TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER RAILROAD TANK CAR (DUPX 20138) AND TRANSPORTED TO DUPONT'S FACILITY IN PARKERSBURG, WEST VIRGINIA TO BE TESTED FOR CONTAMINATION. APPROXIMATELY 300 TONS OF CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS COLLECTED AND WILL BE SHIPPED TO A CERTIFIED LANDFILL ON NIAGARA FALLS, NEW YORK.

ON FRIDAY, JULY 26TH, GIBRALTAR RECEIVED A LOAD OF CUPRIC CHLORIDE FROM IBM'S AUSTIN FACILITY.  AFTER LOADING, THE TRUCK MOVED TO THE IBM TRUCK SCALES.  SOMETIME AFTER THE TRUCK HAD LEFT THE FACILITY, IBM PERSONNEL NOTICED SOME CUPRIC CHLORIDE ON THE PAVEMENT ON IBM PROPERTY AND ON THE FEEDER ROAD AT MOPAC BLVD.  WHEN GIBRALTAR WINONA PERSONNEL WERE NOTIFIED OF THE PROBLEM, SUBSEQUENT INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE AIR VALVE ON TOP OF THE TRUCK HAD BEEN LEFT OPEN AND THAT SOME MATERIAL HAD SPLASHED OUT. REWEIGHING OF THE TRUCK REVEALED THAT ONLY A MINOR AMOUNT HAD BEEN LOST.

THE COLLISION RIPPED OPEN OUR TRUCK'S FUEL TANK.  A FIRE RESULTED.  BOTH TRUCKS WERE TOTAL BURNS.  WE DO NOT PLAN TO TRANSPORT ORANGE OIL IN THE NEAR FUTURE.

column168: DRIVER WAS WESTBOUND ON I-265 NEAR LOUISVILLE, KY.  THE TANK OVERTURNED AS A RESULT OF AN ACCIDENT.  THE TRAILER THOUGH SEROUSLY DAMAGED DID NOT RUPTURE.  THE TRAILER ENDED UPON ITS SIDE AND THERE WAS SLIGHT SEEPAGE OF PRODUCT FROM A VALVE (LESS THAN ONE POUND).  MOST OF THE DECONTAMINATION CLEAN UP COSTS INVOLVED DIESEL FUEL AND GASOLINE WHICH IGNITED FROM THE FUEL TANKS OF THE VEHICLES.  HERITAGE REMEDIATION WAS CALLED TO THE SCENE FOR CLEAN UP.  DRIVER INVOLVED IN THE ACCIDENT WAS TERMINATED.  THE TANK VESSEL PERFORMANCE WAS EXCELLENT CONSIDERING THE IMPACT.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: THE TRAILER FAILURE WAS DUE TO AN IMPROPERLY MARKED COMPARTMENT.  THE 2750 COMPARTMENT WAS PAINTED AS 2800 ON THE TOP OF THE TANK. BECAUSE OF THE OVERFILL OF THIS COMPARTMENT THE VAPOR RECOVERY TUBE WAS FULL.  THE TRAILER WAS LOCATED ON A SLOPED AREA AND WHEN THE DROP TUBE WAS HOOKED UP AND THE COMPARTMENT VALVE HANDLES WERE OPENED THE MANIFOLD TUBE WAS FULL AS THE PRODUCT SOUGHT ITS OWN LEVEL.  THE DRIVER WAS GOING TO DROP THE REAR AND FRONT COMPARTMENTS AT THE SAME TIME AND HAD NOT OPENED THE HANDLE ON THE DROP THUS CREATING THE PROBLEM THAT RESULTED IN THE SPILL. ACCORDING TO HIS FIGURES INDICATION WERE THAT APPROXIMATELY 11 GALLONS WAS SPILLED.

CARTON FELL BACK ONTO TRAILER FLOOR WHEN PALLET LOADED BEHIND SHIPMENT WAS REMOVED.  5 PINT GLASS JAR BROKE AND CONTENTS SPILLED.  SPILLAGE WAS CONTAINED AND ABSORBED WITH FLOOR DRY AND REPLACED IN RECOVERY DRUM. REMAINING BOTTLES (5) WERE INTACT AND RECEIVED BY CONSIGNEE.

column168: THIS IS TO INFORM YOU THAT WE HAD A LEAKING TANK CAR AT OUR NORTH YARD #19. AT APPROX. 2:15 PM MECH. FOREMAN JAMES YOUNG INFORMED ME THAT GATX 83831 WAS LEAKING FROM THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE DUE TO INTERNAL PRESSURE AND THE CAR WAS OVERLOADED. THE CAR WAS SPOTTED ON #48, SOUTH END TO TRANSFER OF PRODUCT.  CUSTOMER SERVICE LOCATED SHIPPER (FARRELL GAS CO).  THEY SENT TANK TRUCK TO TRANSFER PRODUCT. THE HOUSTON FIRE DEPT HAZ MAT TEAM WAS TO ASSIST IN TRANSFERRING OF PRODUCT.  THE YARD PERSONNEL WAS EVACUATED TO THE SOUTH END OF YARD.  ALL OPERATIONS WAS HALTED FROM 5:30 PM UNTIL 7:15 PM. AT 7:15 PM RESUME NORMAL OPERATIONS WITH EXCEPTION OF THE F.  LEAD WAS SHUT DOWN WHILE TANK TRUCK TRANSFER APPRX. 20% OF PRODUCT INTO TANK TRUCK. AT 7:45 THE TRANSFER WAS COMPLETED AND RESUME OPERATIONS OF THE ENTIRE YARD.

ON TUESDAY 31 JULY, 1991, A DRIVER OF ANKER TRUCKING COMPANY, WHO WAS CONTRACTED TO ENVIRITE CORPORATION, WAS LOADING A FULL ROLL-OFF CONTAINER OF TREATMENT RESIDUAL ONTO A ROLL-OFF TRAILER AT THE SHIPPER'S SITE. AS THE LOADED ROLL-OFF BOX WAS BEING HOISTED ONTO THE TRAILER, THE LADING SHIFTED AND APPROXIMATELY TWO (2) CUBIC YARDS OF IT PASSED OVER THE BOX'S GASKETED TAILGATE AND UNDER THE PORTION OF THE TARP CONTACTING THE TAILGATE.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL FELL ONTO THE PAVED LOADING AREA, AND IT WAS PROMPTLY CLEANED UP.  THE SPILL WAS NOT THE RESULT OF A PACKAGE FAILURE; RATHER IT RESULTED FROM THE CONSIGNOR'S IMPROPER LOADING OF A STRUCTURALLY SOUND PACKAGE.  THE PAVED PARKING AREA PREVENTED THE SPILL'S CONTACT WITH THE ENVIRONMENT.  NO INJURIES OR PROPERTY DAMAGE RESULTED FROM THE INCIDENT. ENVIRITE CORPORATION BELIEVES THAT THE SPILL IS THE RESULT OF TWO FACTORS: 1) THE ROLL-OFF BOX WAS OVERFILLED BY THE SHIPPER, AND 2) THE ROLL-OFF BOX'S LADING WAS TOO WET.  ACCORDING TO THE CONTRACT CARRIER (ANKER TRUCKING), THE DRIVER VISUALLY CHECKED THE PHYSICAL STATE OF THE LOAD AND CONCLUDED THAT IT WAS SUITABLE FOR TRANSPORT.  APPARENTLY, THE LADING'S LIQUID PORTION WAS NOT READILY OBSERVABLE. THE LOAD REMAINED AT THE SHIPPER'S SITE AND, THEREFORE, DID NOT BECOME THE SUBJECT OF ACTIVE SHIPPING PAPERS ON JULY 31, 1991. ENVIRITE HAS SINCE ADVISED THE CONSIGNOR TO MONITOR BOTH MOISTURE CONTENT AND LOAD VOLUME IN THE FUTURE AND IT HAS STRESSED TO ANKER TRUCKING COMPANY THE IMPORTANCE OF CONTINUALLY CHECKING THE CONTENTS OF A ROLL-OFF BOX BEFORE HOISTING THE BOX ONTO A TRAILER.

CONTAINER WAS FOUND LEAKING IN SHOPS AREA, THEN PLACED IN SAFE LOCATION & THEN LATER AT THE DOCK TO OFF LOAD.  RESPONDERS USED 'SCB' & LEVEL C PROTECTIVE CLOTHING.  THE LOAD WAS FAK, INCLUDING 10-55 GALLON STEEL DRUMS EACH CONTAINING 1,1-TRICHLOROETHANE; PERCHLOROETHYLENE & OTHER PACKAGES CONTAINING NON-FLAMMABLE COMPRESSED GAS, NITROGEN; COMPRESSED GAS, FLAMMABLE NOS (METHYLENE CHLORIDE & VARIOUS NON-HAZARDOUS ITEMS).  THE LADING HAD BEEN PLACED IN A THROUGH LOAD WHICH WAS TIGHT LATERALLY & LONGITUDINALLY.  ONLY A FEW UNITS WERE PLACED IN THE INCOMPLETE 2ND LAYER.  THE DRUMS AT THE REAR, THE LEFT ROW HAD 6 DRUMS ON THE FLOOR IN 2 ROWS & 3 STACKS THEN 1 PALLET OF 4 DRUMS, THE RIGHT ROW HAD TWO DRUMS ON THE FLOOR AT THE REAR, 1 PALLET OF 4 DRUMS THEN 4 DRUMS ON THE FLOOR.  AT THIS POINT BOX ITEMS BEGAN.  THE 2 RIGHT ROW DRUMS ON THE THE PALLET IN THE LEFT ROW WERE LEAKERS ACCOUNT METAL FATIGUE FROM CONTACT WITH THE 2 LEFT ROW DRUMS IN THE RIGHT ROW FORWARD STACKS.  THE TOP ROLLING HOOPS OF THE DRUMS ON THE FLOOR MADE CONTACT WITH SIDES OF 2 DRUMS ON THE LEFT ROW PALLET.  THE 2 LEAKING DRUMS WERE PLACED IN RECOVERY DRUMS & RETURNED TO LOAD.  LOAD WILL BE SORTED AT THE HARBOR.

column168: THE DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE CONSIGNEE'S SITE FOR DELIVERY.  THE STORE ATTENDANT TOOK STICK READINGS, ALONG WITH THE DRIVER, OF THE STORAGE TANK TO BE FILLED.  THE STORE ATTENDANT ADVISED THE DRIVER IT WAS OK TO DROP, THAT THE TANK WOULD HOLD ALL THE PRODUCT HE HAD TO DELIVER.  THE DRIVER THEN HOOKED UP HIS FITTINGS AND BEGAN UNLOADING, THE TANK OVERFILLED AND DRIVER SHUT OFF THE EMERGENCY VALVE TO TRAILER TO STOP THE FLOW OF PRODUCT. ABOUT 3-5 GALLONS SPILLED ONTO THE CONCRETE SLAB OF THE FUEL ISLAND.  THE STORE ATTENDENT CALL THE LOCAL FIRE DEPT. AND THEY ARRIVED AND USED OIL DRY TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL AND LEFT.  THE DRIVER WAS AT THE WRONGCIRCLE K STORE AND DIDN'T KNOW HE WASN'T GOING TO RECEIVE THE LOAD AND JUST FOLLOWED INSTRUCTIONS OF HIS MANAGERS.  THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED REGARDING THIS INCIDENT AND TOLD TO FOLLOW COMPANY POLICY AND PROCEDURES AS INSTRUCTED TO INSURE HE WAS AT THE CORRECT DESTINATION AND THAT THEY COULD HOLD ALL PRODUCT DELIVERED.

column168: THE DRIVER HAD COMPLETED MAKING DELIVERY OF GASOLINE AND HAD DISCONNECTED HIS VAPOR RECOVERY HOSE FROM THE TRUCK AND HELD IT UP TO DRAIN ANY RESIDUE FROM THE HOSE BACK TO THE TANK. HE LAID THE END OF THE HOSE ON THE PAVEMENT AND DISCONNECTED THE OTHER END OF THE HOSE WHICH HE HAD LAID ON THE DRIVEWAY AND WENT TOWARD A STORM DRAIN. IT APPEARED A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT MAY HAVE GONE INTO THE STORM DRAIN. THE STORM DRAIN CONTAINED ONLY DIRT AND WHEN IT WAS CLEANED OUT THERE DID NOT APPEAR TO BE ANY GAS PRESENT. THE GAS ON THE DRIVEWAY WAS CLEANED UP WITH SORBENT PADS. THE REASON FOR THIS OCCURENCE WAS THE FACT THAT THE TANKS HAD PREVIOUSLY BEEN FILLED TO CAPACITY, INCLUDING ALL FILL LINES AND VAPOR LINES. THE VAPOR LINE STILL CONTAINED PRODUCT AND A SMALL AMOUNT HAD GOTTEN BACK INTO THE HOSE. ONCE DELIVERIES WERE MADE THE PRODUCT CLEARED ITSELF FROM THE VAPOR LINE AND THIS SHOULD NO OCCUR AGAIN.

column168: ON JULY 2, 1991 I WAS MAKING A DELIVERY TO STREATER IND, ALBERT LEA, MN FROM OUR TERMINAL IN ST. PAUL, MN. WHEN BACKING INTO THE DOCK I SAW TRAIL OF PAINT LEAKING FROM THE TRAILER.  I GOT OUT OF TRACTOR AND OPENED TRAILER DOORS, DISCOVERED SPILL, PAINT WAS LEAKING OUT ON FLOOR OF TRAILER FORM THE 55 GAL DRUMS.  I NOTIFIED THE RECEIVING CLERK OF THE PAINT LEAK, WHO IN TURN NOTIFIED HIS SUPERVISOR, SUPERVISOR NOTIFIED DENNIS SERSHEN, CHMM MANAGER OF FACILITIES ENGR.  I THEN NOTIFIED MY DISPATCH AT GRAND RAPIDS MI.  I THEN TALKED TO ALLAN BISHOP, PRESIDENT OF TML INC.  I THEN CALLED STEVEN LEE AT M.P.C.A., STEVEN LEE GAVE ME THE TELEPHONE NUMBER OF TWO COMPANIES TO CALL FOR CLEAN-UP.  I CONTACTED BOTH COMPANIES.  OHM CORPORATION, NEW HOPE MN WAS THE COMPANY THAT WAS BROUGHT IN FOR CLEAN-UP THEY COULD RESPOND THE FASTEST.  THEY ARRIVED AT 4:30 AND INSPECTED ALL DRUMS.  THREE OF THE TWENTY DRUMS WERE LEAKING.  TWO WERE INSPECTED TO MAKE SURE NOTHING WAS LEAKING BEFORE I RETURNED TO ST PAUL, I THEN LEFT FOR ST. PAUL, ON THE WAY BACK I STOPPED THREE TIMES TO MAKE SURE IT WAS NOT LEAKING.  RETURNED TO ST. PAUL AT 10:00 P.M.  TRAILER WAS RETURNED TO GRAND RAPIDS TERMINAL ON JULY 4, 1991 AS ALL FREIGHT WAS REFUSED.  THIS WILL THEN BE RETURNED TO SHIPPER GUARDSMAN CHEMICAL AT GRAND RAPIDS, MI.

YOUNG WAS INFORMED BY YARDMASTER ELLISON THAT THERE WAS A CAR LEAKING AT OUR PASADENA YARD. UPON ARRIVAL AT PASADENA YARD AN INSPECTION WAS MADE FOUND TO BE (3) THREE CARS LEAKING. AT THIS TIME MR. MAGEE ARRIVED AT SCENE AND BETWEEN MR. MAGEE AND MR. YOUNG SECURED THE SCENE AND ALL OPERATIONS AT OUR PASADENA YARD HALTED UNTIL FURTHER EVALUATION WERE MADE. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED (PETRO CHEMICALS) MR. ROBERT L. TABUENA FOR PETRO CHEMICALS ARRIVED AT SCENE.  ON ARRIVAL MR. TABUENA CALLED EM TECH COMPANY FOR FURTHER CONSULTATION.  THEY ARRIVED AT SCENE AND MADE INSPECTION OF CARS AND AGREED THAT TRANSFER OF PRODUCT WAS NEEDED DUE TO THE CARS BEING OVERLOADED. AN EMPTY TANK CAR (L.P.G.) WAS NEEDED FOR TRANSFERRING OF PRODUCT.  FOUND ONE IN LUBRIZOL (GATX 97296.  THE 3 LEAKING TANK CARS WERE SPOTTED ON SOUTH END OF TRACK NO. 15.  UPON ARRIVAL OF THE EMPTY TANK THE CAR WAS SPOTTED ON THE SOUTH END OF TRACK NO. 14. AT APPROXIMATELY 5 P.M. I RELIEVED MR. MAGE AND MR. YOUNG AND ASSUMED COMMAND OF THE SCENE AND SECURED ALL OPERATIONS ON THE SOUTH END OF YARD BETWEEN TRACKS 12 THRU 15. TRANSFERRING OF PRODUCT STARTED AT 7 P.M. UNTIL 11:15 PM.  RESUMED NORMAL OPERATIONS AT 12:30 A.M. THE CARS INVOLVED ARE: ACFX 17173 ROUTE VIA SP-PTRA-LUBRIZOL; ACFX 17373 ROUTE VIA SP-PTRA-LUBRIZOL ACFX; 18752 ROUTE VIA SP-PTRA-LUBRIZOL.

column168: HAZARDOUS MATERIAL WAS IN TRAILER 17-7222 INBOUND TO THE CHEYENNE CONSOLIDATION CENTER TO BE BROKEN DOWN.  BRAD DRIER, DOCKWORKER, OPENED THIS TRAILER AND INHALED GASEOUS FUMES OF WHICH HE WAS UNAWARE OF.  BRAD CONTACTED HIS FOREMEN ON DUTY DEAN HOFFMAN.  DEAN WALKED INTO THIS TRAILER AND ALSO INHALED FUMES.  FOREMAN MATT GREEN WALKED BY THIS SAME TRAILER ANS ASKED WHAT THE SITUATION WAS AND DISCOVERED BY LOOKING AT THE BILL OF LADING THAT THEY SHOULD INVESTIGATE WHAT THE GAS WAS.  MATT CLOSED THE TRAILER AND PUT IT OUT IN THE YARD UNTIL WE COULD FIND OUT WHAT WAS LEAKING. I GOT INVOLVED AND LOOKED UP IN THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL THE UN NUMBER, ETHYLENE OXIDE UN 1040, IN THE US DOT EMERGENCY RESPONSE GUIDEBOOK.  AFTER READING THE POTENTIAL HAZARDS AND EMERGENCY ACTIONS NEEDED, I TRIED CONTACTING THE SHIPPER.  DUE TO THE HOLIDAY, I CALLED CHEM TREC FOR HELP. CHEM TREC FAXED COPIES OF THE MSDS AND HAD ME SEND BRAD DRIER AND SEAN HOFFMAN TO THE HOSPITAL FOR CHECKUP. FOLLOWING THAT, THEY HAD ME CALL THE FIRE DEPARTMENT TO INVESTIGATE AND DETAIN THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT STARTED USING A SOAP SOLUTION SUSPECTING A LEAK IN ONE OF THE VALVES IN 55 GALLON TANKS.  THEY DIDN'T DETECT ANYTHING AND CALLED THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL MANAGER FOR UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD TO USE HIS GAS DETECTING DEVICE "SNIFFER" TO FIND THE GAS LEAK.  THEY FOUND ONE TANK WITH A SLIGHT LEAK IN ONE OF THE VALVES.  THE VALVE WAS TIGHTENED AND THE INCIDENT DETAINED. BRAD DRIER AND DEAN HOFFMAN WERE CHECKED OUT AT THE HOSPITAL OKAY, AND SAID THEY WOULD CONTINUE TO HAVE A HEADACHE FOR A FEW MORE HOURS.  THEY WERE TOLD TO REST, GET PLENTY OF FRESH AIR AND DRINK PLENTY OF LIQUIDS. OKAY TO RETURN TO WORK 7-5-91.

NLASZ-30 TRAIN CREW REPORTED THAT THEIR TRAIN HAD DERAILED ON THE MACARTHUR BRIDGE ON THE TERMINAL RAILROAD CARROLL STREET APPROACH.  TANK CAR UTLX 820045 LPG (RESIDUE) WAS ONE OF FOUR CARS DERAILED. ST. LOUIS FIRE CHIEF N. SVETANICS RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE ORDERED AN EVACUATION OF THE IMMEDIATE AREA INCLUDING THE GATEWAY ARCH AREA.  INTERSTATE TRAFFIC ON I44 & I55 ALSO WAS STOPPED.  COAST GUARD WAS NOTIFIED TO STOP ALL WATER TRAFFIC ON THE MISSISSIPPI. UPRR SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS C. SHUPE, TOGETHER WITH MEMBERS OF THE ST. LOUIS CITY FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SQUAD, INSPECTED THE DERAILEMENT SITE AND DETERMINED THAT NO HAZARDOUS MATERIALS WERE RELEASED AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT.

column168: SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS T.H. SMITH TRAVELED TO LAREDO TO INSPECT TRAILER REAZ 257142 AND FOUND AN 8"X8" SPILL OF LIQUID BENEATH THE CAR.  SSA/HM SMITH HOSED DOWN THE ASPHALT, AND NOTIFIED TEXAS WATER COMMISSION AND TRAIN MANAGEMENT, AND ARRANGED FOR EMTECH EMERGENCY SERVICES.  AT 2210 HOURS, TRAILER WAS ENTERED AND SSA/HM SMITH DETERMINED THE LOAD OF 74 FIFTY-FIVE GALLON DRUMS HAD ALL SHIFTED TOWARD THE DOORS OF THE TRAILER DUE TO THE LACK OF BLOCKING AND BRACING. THE LOAD WAS BLOCKED WITH A SINGLE 2X4 NAILED TO THE FLOOR AT THE REAR OF THE LOAD.  ONE OF THE BRACE NAILS CAUSED THE BOTTOM CHIME ON DRUM #16 TO SEPARATE.  THE LEAK WAS CLOSED BY HAMMERING THE OPENING SHUT AND APPLYING EPOXY TO AN ALUMINUM TAPE PATCH.  THE DRUM WAS THEN OVERPACKED AND SURROUNDED BY SORBENT IN THE OVERPACK.  THE TRAILER WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT.

column168: UP SENIOR SEPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS D. COOPER WAS INFORMED BY TAILBOARD YARDMASTER AT YERMO (FRANK VALDEZ) THAT MATERIAL WAS LEAKING FROM A FITTING ON THE TOP OF TANK CAR GATX 73794, WHILE MOVING FROM TRACK #9.  SMALL FIRES ERUPTED AS THE PRODUCT HIT THE GROUND.  TWO YARD ENGINE CREW MEMBERS WERE EXPOSED TO THE SMOKE AND ASKED TO BE TAKEN TO BARSTOW COMMUNITY HOSPITAL WHERE THEY WERE EXAMINED AND RELEASED. TANK CAR GATX 73794 HAD BEEN RECEIVED FROM SOUTHERN PACIFIC RAILROAD AT COLTON, CA INTERCHANGE POINT AT 1700 HOURS, JULY 8, 1991.  INSPECTION OF THE CAR BY SSA/HM COOPER REVEALED THE RUPTURE DISC IN THE SAFETY VENT HAD BURST.  AFTER REPLACING THE RUPTURE DISC, THE EXTERIOR OF THE CAR WAS HOSED DOWN TO REMOVE ANY RESIDUAL PRODUCT.  INSPECTION OF THE REMAINING VALVES AND FITTINGS FOUND ALL TO BE SECURE.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT TO CONSIGNEE.  THE BLOWN RUPTURE DISC WAS GIVEN TO THE CASUALTY MANAGEMENT GROUP IN LOS ANGELES PER THEIR REQUEST.

column168: AT 10:10 A.M., TUESDAY, JULY 16, 1991, THE ACCA YARD CREW REPORTED TO THE YARDMASTER THAT TANK CAR GATX 44984 WAS LEAKING FROM AROUND THE FITTINGS ON TOP OF THE TANK CAR WHILE IT WAS BEING MOVED.  THE TANK CAR WAS PROMPTLY ISOLATED IN THE EAST YARD (PIGGYBACK RAMP TRACK) UNTIL REPAIRS COULD BE MADE.  UPON NOTIFICATION, MR. J.R. HALL, ASSISTANT ENGINEER, INSPECTED THE TANKCAR AND FOUND THAT IT HAD BEEN SEEPING FROM THE FITTING CONTAINING THE SAFETY PRESSURE RELIEF DISC.  NO PONDING OR GROUND ACCUMULATION WAS EVIDENT.  APPARENTLY THE SLIGHT SEEPAGE ONLY WHILE THE CAR WAS IN MOTION.  MR.  WILLIAM J OERTLY, JR., DISTRICT INSPECTOR FOR THE AAR'S BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES WAS CONTACTED AT 10:20 A.M., AND MR. OERTLY ADVISED THAT HE COULD RESPOND TO MAKE THE NECESSARY REPAIRS TO THE TANK CAR.  CHEMTREC WAS CONTACTED AT 10:25 A.M., AND THEY, IN TURN, CONTACTED THE SHIPPER, S.T. SERVICES, INC., OF BALTIMORE, MARYLAND.  MR OERTLY ARRIVED AT ACCA YARD AT 1:00 P.M. AND DETERMINED THAT THE LEAK WAS DUE TO A RUPTURED SAFETY PRESSURE DISC.  THE DISC WAS REPLACED AND CAR WAS RETURNED TO SERVICE.  THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISED THAT THE TANK CAR HAD BEEN REPAIRED AND WAS BEING RETURNED TO NORMAL SERVICE AT 2:00 P.M.

column168: THE UP TERMINAL TRAILER FACILITY AT OAKLAND, CA REPORTED TO UPRR SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DENNIS ALM THAT TRAILER VTRZ 237136 WAS LEAKING.  SSA/HM ALM'S INSPECTION ON 7/13/91 REVEALED THERE HAD BEEN A LOAD SHIFT INSIDE THE TRAILER AND THE CONTENTS HAD MOVED TO THE REAR, PUTTING PRESSURE ON THE 50-GALLON DRUMS AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  TWO 50-GALLON DRUMS OF CHLORINATING BACTERICIDE DISINFECTANT AND DEODORANT WERE SQUEEZED BY OTHER DRUMS AND HAD LEAKED A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT THROUGH THE SMAL HOLE IN THE TOP BUNG.  WHEN THE REAR DOORS OF THE TRAILER WERE OPENED, THE DRUMS AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER EXPANDED, AND THE REAR DOORS WERE NOT ABLE TO BE CLOSED.  SSA/HM ALM TIED A ROPE BETWEEN THE DOORS AND SECURED THE TRAILER.  ON JULY 13, SSA/HM ALM NOTIFIED CHEMTREC AND CALIFORNIA OES, AS WELL AS ECOLAB (CHEMIST JIM DECKER).  ON JULY 16, ECOLAB REPRESENTATIVES REMOVED THE TWO 50-GALLON DRUMS THAT HAD LEAKED AND REBRACED THE TRAILER.  SINCE THE SMALL AMOUNT OF APILLED COMMODITY WAS WATER-SOLUBLE, ECOLAB CHEMIST JIM DECKER ORDERED THE AREA WASHED WITH WATER.  THE TRAILER WAS RELEASED FROM OAKLAND INTERMODAL FACILITY AT 1430HR. ON 7/16/91.

column168: NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER - INCIDENT #79052.   CAL OIL SPILL GROUP, FISH AND GAME, EPA, RGWCDB REPORT #18020.  CAL OSHA REPORT #361272206. OPINIONS  & CONCLUSIONS:  V-1 WAS N/B SR 99 APPROX 55 MPH.  (THE TACH-O-GRAPH FOUND IN V-1 INDICATED A SPEED OF 57-58 MPH - USING AN AVG. OF 150' OF LOCKED DUAL WHEEL SKIDS INDICATES A SPEED OF APPROX 56 MPH AND WIT #1 VERIFIES FOLLOWING V-1 AT 55 MPH.)  SR 99 WAS UNDER CONSRUCTION FOR RESURFACING.  APPROXIMATELY 8 VEHS HAD BEEN STOPPED BY A FLAGMAN N/B SR 99 AT THE SOUTH END OF THE TAHITIAN GARDENS GOLF DRIVING RANGE.  THESE VEHS HAD BEEN AT A COMPLETE STOP FOR SEVERAL MINUTES.  DRI, PROBABLY DUE TO INATTENTION ON HIS PART, FAILED TO NOTICE THAT ALL TRAFFIC HAD STOPPED IN FRONT OF HIM.  WHEN HE FINALLY REALIZED THAT HE WAS REARING DOWN ON THE STOPPED TRAFFIC AND THAT HE WAS TRAVELLING TOO FAST TO STOP BEHIND IT HE APPLIED HIS BRAKES AND SWERVED TO THE RIGHT TRYING TO PASS TRAFFIC ON THE EAST SHOULDER.  THERE WAS NOT ENOUGH ROOM BETWEEN THE CARS AND A PC & E POWER POLE.  V-1 STRUCK V-5 IN THE RR FENDER PROPELLING IT ACROSS SR99 ONTO THE S.B SIDE.  V-1 THEN STRUCK V-4 PROPELLING IT LIKEWISE.  THE SAME OCCURRED TO V-3.  AT ABOUT THE TIME V-1 WAS COLLIDING INTO THE RIGHT SIDES OF V-4 & V-3, IT STRUCK A POWER POLE TO ITS RIGHT BREAKING IT IN HALF AND SENDING A TRANSFORMER TO THE DROUND.  THE WHEELS OF V-1 ENTERED A DRAINAGE DITCH CAUSING A LOSS OF STEERING CONTROL.  V-1 ARCHED TO THE LEFT AND DUE TO THE WEIGHT OF ITS LOADED TANKS OVERTURNED COMING TO REST UNSIDE DOWN ON TOP OF V-2.  THE TRAILER OF V-1 STRUCK A 2 AXLE BOBTAIL TRUCK (V-7) AT 4444 SAWTELLE AV.  A FRONT TIRE ON V-1 ALSO SMASHED THE R. TAIL GATE AND WINDOW OF V-6 WHICH WAS STOPPED AHEAD OF V-2 JUST BEFORE COMING TO REST. DRIVER #1 CAUSED THIS COLLISION AND IS IN VIOLATION IF 22350 I.E.   UNSAFE SPEED FOR CONDITIONS (CONSTRUCTION ZONE & STOPPED TRAFFIC) AND 192(C)(2) P.C. - MISDEMEANOR MANSLAUGHTER. V-2.  THE T

column168: ON TUESDAY, JULY 23, 1991, AT APPROXIMATELY 1000 HOURS, WHILE MAKING AN INSPECTION OF A TANK CAR ON TRAIN CSXT HOPEWELL TURN, RF&P ASSISTANT ENGINEER J.R. HALL DISCOVERED TANK CAR GATX 7322 SEEPING ITS CONTENTS FROM THE FITTINGS CONTAINING THE SAFETY PRESSURE RELIEF DISC.  NO PONDING OF GROUND ACCUMULATION WAS EVIDENT.  APPARENTLY THE SLIGHT SEEPAGE ONLY OCCURRED WHILE THE CAR WAS IN MOTION. THE TANK CAR, GATX 7322, WAS REMOVED FROM THE TRAIN AND ISOLATED IN THE EAST YARD (PIGGYBACK RAMP TRACK) UNTIL REPAIRS COULD BE MADE. CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED AT 1010 HOURS AND THEY, IN TURN, NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER, PERIDOT CHEMICALS OF 5501 PENNINGTON AVENUE, BALTIMORE (CURTIS BAY) MARYLAND 21226. RALPH IACOBELLI OF PERIDOT CHEMICALS CALLED AT 1030 HOURS AND ADVISED HE WOULD CONTACT GENERAL RAILWAY SERVICE AT SUFFOLK, VIRGINIA, TO RESPOND AND MAKE REPAIRS TO THE TANK CAR. REPRESENTATIVES OF GENERAL RAILWAY SERVICES ARRIVED AT ACCA YARD AND IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK WAS A RUPTURED SAFETY PRESSURE RELIEF DISC.  THE DISC WAS REPLACED AND REPAIRS WERE COMPLETED ON TANK CAR GATX 7322 AT 1500 HOURS, AND THE CAR WAS PLACED BACK INTO NORMAL RAIL SERVICE.

AT APPROXIMATLEY 1700. 7-23-91. LCD DRIVER RICHARD MEINTS NOTICED AN ODOR BETWEEN HIS TRAILERS WHILE PERFORMING HIS PRE-TRIP.  DISPATCHER DAVE THORNTON WAS NOTIFIED OF THE PROBLEM.  DAVE CONTACTED DOCK FOREMAN TOM REIDY, WHO CALLED THE CHEYENNE FIRE DEPARTMENT.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1745 THE CHEYENNE FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED AND STARTED GATHERING INFORMATION ON THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL IN THE MATERIAL IN THE TRAILER.  THE TRAILER 11-3525 PLACARDED POISON GAS CONTAINED A 15LB. CYLINDER OF RESIDUE LAST CONTAINED ARSINE, POISON A, UN2188.  AFTER ALL INFORMATION WAS GATHERED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WEARING PROTECTIVE CLOTHING, OPENED THE TRAILER, DETECTED A LOOSE VALVE, AND CLOSED THE VALVE.  CHEYENNE DRIVER ROGER BUTTON WHO BROUGHT THE LOAD INTO CHEYENNE WAS TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL FOR OBSERVATION, ANETHE LINCOLN DRIVER RICHARD MEINTS AND DISPATCHER DAVE THORNTON WERE TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL FOR OBSERVATION.  JOSE AROCHO WITH SOLKATRONIC IN MORRISVILLE, PA, FLEW INTO CHEYENNE THE FOLLOWING DAY TO TEST AND DETERMINE IF A CONTAMINATION CLEANUP WAS NEEDED.  WE WERE INFORMED THAT THERE WAS NO CONTAMINATION.

column168: ADVISED BY CSX OPS. M. ANDERS THAT THE YARD CREW MOVING CAR GATX 18468 MOTED PRODUCT SPLASH FROM THE TOP FITTINGS ON THE CAR.  CAR WAS ISOLATED IN #3 DRILL TRACK.  CHEMTREC CONTACTED AND SHIPPER ADVISED OF INCIDENT. ARRANGEMENTS MADE BY SHIPPER TO HAVE GATX MOBILE REPAIR SERVICE TO RESPOND AND INSPECT AND SECURE CAR.  GATX SECURED AND REPAIRED CAR ON 07/25/91 0730 HRS BY REPLACING THE RUPTURED SAFETY VENT DISC, AND CAR RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT TO DESTINATION.

AT APPROXIMATELY 1645 HOURS MONDAY, JULY 22, 1991, DOT/FRA HAZARDOUS MATERIALS INSPECTORS CONLEY AND KEISTER OBSERVED TANK CAR GATX-300420 LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE MANWAY AREA AS CAR WAS DEPARTING THE CONRAIL COLUMBUS, OHIO "BUCKEYE" RAIL YARD IN TRAIN COBU-5.  TANK CAR WAS SET OUT OF TRAIN AND ISOLATED ON THE PHILLIPS 66 SIDING TRACK.  CHEMTREC AND SHIPPER NOTIFIED.  CONRAIL GENERAL CAR FOREMAN G.A. SZEBIN INSPECTED THE CAR AT APPROXIMATELY 1745 HOURS AND FOUND THAT ALL EIGHT (8) MANWAY BOLTS WERE LOOSE AND ALLOWING PRODUCT TO ESCAPE.  MANWAY BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED (3/4 TURN EACH) AND CAR WAS CLEARED TO DESTINATION AT 1700 HOURS, JULY 22, 1991.

AT 3:30 A.M., STEVE SCHNEIDER, MIDNIGHT HUB MANAGER, WAS NOTIFIED THAT A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL BOX WAS LEAKING. STEVE TOOK IT UPON HIMSELF TO MOVE THE SPILL TO THE DAMAGE AREA.  HE THEN CALLED CHEMTREC AND WAS TOLD TO CALL THE MIDDLESEX HAZARDOUS MATERIAL TEAM WHICH ARRIVED AT 4:45 A.M. WITH A TOTAL OF FIFTEEN EMERGENCY VEHICLES, HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RESPONSE, EDISON FIRE DEPARTMENT, PLUS AMBULANCES.  THE ENTIRE AREA, WITHIN A QUARTER OF A MILE, WAS EVACUATED AND ROPED OFF. NINE UPS PERSONNEL WERE EVACUATED WITH NO HARM. STEVE SCHNEIDER WAS TAKEN TO JFK HOSPITAL FOR A "BLOOD GASES" TEST AND WAS FOUND TO BE OKAY. THE (2) TWO PINTS THAT HAD SPILLED, ALONG WITH THE TWO BOXES, WERE PLACED IN A FIBER HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DRUM AND SEALED. THE CONTAMINATED FILLERS AND THE WOODEN BOXES WERE PLACED IN A METAL 55-GALLON DRUM. THE CLEAR VENTURE INC. WAS CALLED AT 9:00 A.M. BECAUSE OF THE HEAT CAUSING GASES COMING FROM THE FIBER DRUM STILL POSED A POSSIBLE THREAT. THEY WERE ALSO CALED TO NEUTRALIZE AND CONTAIN ALL OF THE SPILLED MATERIAL BECAUSE OF THE POTENTIAL HAZARDOUS MATERIAL THREAT. THE CLEAR VENTURE TEAM ARRIVED AT 10:45 A.M. THE COMPANY FIELD SUPERVISOR, CHARLES M. LAKATOS, ALONG WITH HIS TEAM, INCLUDING A CHEMIST, INSPECTED EVERY BOTTLE AND SAW NO DETERIORATION OF THE REMAINING 12 BOTTLES IN THE SIX REMAINING CARTONS WHICH THEY THEN REPACKED, RETAPED, AND GAVE US PERMISSION TO FORWARD ON TO THE CONSIGNEE. THE TEAM THEN WENT THROUGH THE DAMAGE PORTION AND REPACKED THE ENTIRE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DRUMS AND CONTAINERS. THEY WILL RETURN ON 7/22/91 FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.

ON 7-25-91 AT ABOUT 6 PM I RETURNED TO THE PROCESS PLANT AFTER A MEETING. A SULFURIC TRUCK WAS IN OUR LOADING DOCK UNLOADING SOME SULFURIC ACID. JOE FROM GENERAL ALARM WAS THERE TALKING TO THE DRIVER OF THE TRUCK. APPROXIMATELY AT 6:05 I WENT OUT TO TALK TO THE DRIVER.  I CHECKED HIS HOSE CONNECTIONS FOR ANY LEAKS.  THERE WERE NONE.  I SHOWED HIM WHERE OUR SHOWER AND EYE WASH STATION WAS.  HE KNEW ALREADY WHERE THEY WERE.  HE WAS WEARING RUBBER GLOVES, A LONG PROTECTIVE JACKET AND A HELMET WITH A SAFETY SHIELD.  I THEN LEFT HIM AND WENT BACK INTO THE PLANT.  I BRIEFLY SPOKE TO HIM TWICE AFTER THAT.  ONCE OUT BY HIS TRUCK AND ONCE INSIDE THE PLANT BEFORE THE INCIDENT OCCURRED.  APPROXIMATELY AT 7:40 PM I HEARD A YELL, I LOOKED OUT OF THE SHIPPING OFFICE WINDOW AND SAW NO ONE AROUND. APPROXIMATELY 15-30 SECS LATER THE DRIVER COME RUNNING INTO THE BUILDING YELLING THAT HIS SKIN WAS BURNING.  HE WAS DISROBED ALREADY.  ALL HE HAD ON WAS HIS UNDERWEAR.  I RAN HIM UPSTAIRS TO OUR LOCKER ROOM AND TURNED THE SHOWER ON HIM.  I THEN RAN BACK DOWNSTAIRS AND TOLD JESSE YATCKOSKI TO GO UP THERE AND STAY WITH HIM.  I ALSO INSTRUCTED LARRY EDEN TO TAKE SOME EYE AND SKIN NEUTRALIZER UP THERE.  I THEN CALLED 911 FOR AN AMBULANCE. AFTER CALLING IT IN I WENT BACK UP THERE TO ASSIST HIM.  HE THEN TOLD ME THAT A VALVE WAS STILL OPEN ON THE TRUCK.  I RAN DOWN TO THE TRUCK TO CLOSE THE VALVE.  I TRIED CLOSING WHICH APPEARED TO BE THE MAIN VALVE BUT IT FELT TO BE MOSTLY CLOSED ALREADY.  I THEN RAN BACK UP STAIRS AND ASKED HIM WHERE THE SHUT OFF VALVE WAS AND HE TOLD ME.  I THEN RAN BACK DOWN STAIRS OUT TO THE TRUCK, CLOSED THE VALVE AND SHUT OFF THE AIR.  THE FLOW OF SULFURIC ACID FROM THE TRUCK WAS LIKE A GARDEN HOSE TURNED WIDE OPEN. APPROXIMATELY 10 MINUTES HAD ELAPSED FROM THE TIME I TOOK THE DRIVER UPSTAIRS TO THE SHOWER TO WHEN I HAD CLOSED THE VALVE ON THE TRUCK AND STOPPED THE FLOW.  THE ACID SPILL WENT IN TWO DIRECTIONS.  SOME MADE IT TO THE STORM SEWER AND SOME DRAINED INTO OUR WASTE TREATMENT CONTAINMENT AREA.  THE TOTAL AMOUNT THAT WENT OUT TO THE STORM SEWER I WOULD GUESS APPROXIMATELY 50 TO 100 GALLONS.  THE WASTE TREATMENT WOULD BE ABOUT THE SAME.  I INSTRUCTED ABOUT FOUR PLANT WORKERS TO SPREAD LIME OVER THE SPILL OUTSIDE TO NEUTRALIZE IT AFTER THE FLOW HAD BEEN STOPPED.

column168: DOCKMAN, GERALD SZYMONIK, WAS UNLOADING THE TRAILER THIS SHIPMENT WAS ON WHEN IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE DRUM WAS LEAKING.  IT WAS THEN ISOLATED AND PUT INTO AN OVERPAK DRUM.

ON 7/10/91, BIRMINGHAM SOUTHERN CREW WAS SWITCHING TANK CAR PLCX 22030 LOADED WITH COAL TAR DISTILLATE.  CONTENTS OF TANK SLOSHED OUT OF DOME ON TOP OF TANK CAR.  TANK CAR WAS REPAIRED ON BIRMINGHAM SOUTHERN PROPERTY BY ALLIED CHEMICAL REPAIRMENT. I TALKED TO MR. DILL AFTER THE INCIDENT.  HE TOLD ME THAT THE LIQUID HAD HIT HIM ON TOP OF HIS HEAD, WHICH WAS COVERED BY A CAP, ROLLED DOWN HIS NECK AND SHOULDERS.  HE IMMDIATELY WENT TO THE CREW LUNCHROOM AND RINSED OFF HIS HEAD AND NECK AS BEST HE COULD.  THEN HE WENT TO THE BATH HOUSE, SHOWERED AND CHANGED CLOTHES.  I INSTRUCTED HIM TO TRY AND KEEP THE RUN OFF OF HIS NECK BY SHIELDING IT WITH A CLOTH OR PAPER TOWEL.  I ALSO TOLD HIM THAT IF IT BOTHERED HIM LATER TO LET US KNOW AND WE WOULD ARRANGE FOR TREATMENT.  ATTACHED ARE COPIES OF THE WAYBILL, FORM 86 HAZARDOUS RESPONSE AND THE CAR INSPECTOR'S REPORT. IT APPEARED AT FIRST THAT THE MANWAY BOLTS WERE JUST LOOSE BUT WHEN ALLIED REPAIRMAN CAME TO 34TH STREET, THEY REPLACED A GASKET ON THE MANWAY AS WELL AS TIGHTENING THE BOLTS.  THE TANK WAS REPAIRED AT 13:00.  FURTHER MECHANICAL QUESTIONS SHOULD BE REFERRED TO DAVID HASKETT AS HE HANDLED THE REPAIRS THROUGH ALLIED.
DRUM ARRIVED CHARLOTTE WITH SMALL CRACK ON BOTTOM OF DRUM.  DRUM PLACED INTO RECOVERY DRUM AND BEING RETURNED TO SHIPPER PER AUTHORITY JIM SLADE.

THE CAR WAS HUMPED INTO 062 TRACK AND THE SOUTH HUMP OPERATOR SAW THE CONTENTS COME OUT AT THE TOP OF THE TANK CAR AS IT WENT THROUGH THE MASTER & GROUP RETARDER.  THIS WAS AT 4:40 P.M. I, MIKE WORS, TRAINMASTER, INSPECTED THE CAR AT 7:15 P.M. AND FOUND MANHOLD BOLTS LOOSE AND I TIGHTENED THEM..  A HAD CAR ISOLATED ON 062 TRACK AND LOCKED OUT.  THE TANK CAR DID NOT LEAK WHEN STANSING STILL NOR DID I GET ANY ODOR.  GASKET NEEDS TO BE CHECKED ON MANHOLE COVER AND PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE NEEDS TO BE CHECKED.  MOISTURE WAS ON BOTH PLACES.  MR. COOPER. SUPERINTENDENT, WAS NOTIFIED AT 9:00P.M. AND WOULD FINISH THE JOB ON DAYLIGHT HOURS.  SEE ATTACHED NOTE OF PERSONNEL.  NO A&S PERSONNEL WERE INJURED.

column42: HAZARDOUS WASTE, LIQUID OR SOLID, N.O.S.
column168: UPRR MOTOR FREIGHT TERMINAL MANAGER T.C. EMMERLING NOTIFIED UPRR SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS C.L HILL THAT DERAMPED TRAILER REAZ 236004 WAS LEAKING AND HAD BEEN MOVED TO UNLOADING DOCK WHERE LOAD WAS REMOVED.  SSA/HM HILL DETERMINED THAT 4 OF THE 16 LARGE CARDBOED BOXES OF PRESSED RAGS WRAPPED IN PALSTIC HAD BEEN DAMAGED DUE TO PRESSURE FROM THE 16 55-GALLON DRUMS WHICH WERE ALSO PART OF THE LOAD.  PLASTIC LINERS WERE BROKEN ALLOWING LIQUID FROM PRESSED RANGES TO LEAK.  ALL SPILLED LIQUID ON FLATCAR, CONCRETE PAD, AND TRAILER WAS PICKED UP WITH ANSORBANT PADS AND FLOOR-DRY AND PLACED WITH 4 DAMAGED CARDBOARD BOXES, WHICH WERE REPACKED INDIVIDUALLY WITH TWO LAYERS OF 10-MILL PLASTIC.  ALL DAMAGED BOXES AND NON-DAMAGED CONTAINERS WERE RELOADED BACK INTO TRAILER AND RELEASED ON TO DESTINATION.  SSA/HM HILL NOTIFIED CHEMTREC AND ADVISED SHIPPER NORTHWEST ENVIRO SERVICE (PAT WEAVER) THAT IN FUTURE THIS TYPE OF LOAD SHOULD HAVE PLYWOOD DIVIDER BETWEEN BOXES AND DRUMS.

column168: WHILE ON A ROUTINE TANK CAR INSEPCTION, UPRR SENOIR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS R.D. FORDEMWALT NOTICED A CLEAR LIQUID DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET OF TANK CAR GATX 22697.  HE DETERMINED THE OUTLET NOZZLE CAP WAS LOOSE (ABLE TO TURN WIHT HAND).  SSA/HM FORDEMWALT TIGHTENDED THE OUTLET NOZZLE AND STOPPED THE DRIPPING LIQUID.  HE FURTHER DETERMINED THE OUTLET OPERATING ROD WAS TIGHTENED DOWN COMPLETELY, PACKING GLAND NUT WAS TIGHT, BUT THERE WAS A LITTLE PLAY IN THE OPERATING ROD. THE LISTED CAR WAS AN EMPTY, PLACARDED "FLAMMBALE RESIDUE" (NA 1986). SSA/HM FORDEMWALT NOTIFIED CHEMTREC (JOE BABER) ON 7/25/91 AT 1310 HOURS (MDT) AND THE SHIPPER ETHANOL MARKETING (HARRY PARISOC) ON 7/26/91 AT 1115 HOURS (MDT).

HILL THAT THE SWITCHMAN AT 400 YARD HAD ADVISED HIM COMMODITY IN TANK CAR DOWX 3365 WAS LEAKING FROM TOP AND RUNNING TO GROUND.  SSA/HM HILL'S INSPECTION (TOGETHER WITH MYIO PENNINGTON) FOUND LIQUID WAS LEAKING FROM SAFETY RELIEF VALVE AND WAS FORMING ICE ON OUTSIDE OF PROTECTIVE HOUSING.  SSA/HM HILL DETERMINED CAR WAS OVERLOADED.  TANK TRUCK WAS USED TO OFF-LOAD 3,000 GALLONS OF CONTENTS; SAFETY VALVE CONTINUED TO LEAK VAPORS.  FURTHER INSPECTION OF SAFETY VALVE DETERMINED ONE OF TWO "O" RINGS WAS DAMAGED., APPARENTLY CAUSED BY ICE BULID-UP WHILE CONTENTS WERE LEAKING.  DAMAGED RING REPALCED WITH NEW "O" RING WHICH STOPPED LEAK.  SSA/HM HILL NOTIFIED CHEMTREC AND EXXON (SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE WILLARD BEARD).  DETERMINED CAUSE OF LEAK WAS DUE TO OVELOADING OF CAR WHICH ALLOWED LIQUID TO LEAK PAST SAFETY VALVE.

UPRR CAR FOREMAN KEN AMOS NOTIFIED UPRR SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS C.E. ZERWECK A SLIGHT VAPOR CLOUD WAS EMANATING FROM TANK CAR GATX 43929.  SSA/HM ZERWECK'S INSPECTION DETERMINED THE FRANGIBLE DISC HAD RUPTURED.  AGENT ZERWECK REPLACED THE 135-POUND DISC WITH AN OSECO 135-POUND DISC.  THE REPAIR WAS ACCOMPLISHED AT 1235 HOURS; AGENT ZERWECK DETERMINED ALL OTHER FITTINGS AND VALVES ON THE CAR WERE SECURE.  SSA/HM ZERWECK NOTIFIED CHEMTREC OF INCIDENT.

column168: NOTIFIED BY REGION H NRC THAT TWO PACKAGES DELIVERED BY DEL-MED DRIVER LINDA SMITH WERE FOUND TO BE GROSSLY CONTAMINATED WITH THALLIUM 201 TO A MAXIMUM LEVEL OF 355,180 DPM/100 CM 2 (59KBG/100CM 2).  THE PACKAGE WERE OTHERWISE UNDAMAGED, INTACT AND WERE NOT CONTAMINATED ON THEIR INNER SURFACES.  THE DRIVER AND HER VIHICLE WERE SURVEYED AND FOUND TO BE UNCONTAMINATED AND NO OTHER PACKAGES DELIVERED ON THE ROUTE WERE REPORTED TO BE CONTAMINATED BY RECEIPT SWIPE SURVEY.  SWIPE DOCUMENTED AS ACCEPTABLE. THE HOSPITAL LABORATORY WHERE THE RECEIPT SURVEY WAS PEFORMED, OR THE SWIPES USED, ARE SUSPECTED TO HAVE BEEN CONTAMINATED WITH T1-201.  THIS IS BEING REPORTED AS THIS IS THE SECOND SUCH OCCURRENCE IN AS MANY MONTHS. THERE WAS NO TRANSPORTATION INCIDENT AND THE MATTER IS BEING FULLY INVESTIGATED BY THE VIRGINIA BUREAU OF RADIOLOGICAL HEALTH.  CONTACT LES FOLESI 804-786-5932 FOR DETAILS.

column168: UPRR OMAHA DISPATCHER JOHN SNYDER NOTIFIED UPRR SENOIR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIAL H.W. RODABAUGH THAT TANK CAR ACFX 89600 WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP WHEN IT WAS IN MOTION.  SSA/HM RODABAUGH INSTRUCTED DISPATCHER SYNDER TO SET OUT THE CAR UNTIL AGENT RODABAUGH COULD GET THERE.  AGENT RODABAUGH'S INSPECTION ON 7/21/91 DETERMINED THE RUPURE DISC WAS DYSFUNCTIONAL.  HE WASHED THE CAR, REPLACED THE RUPTURE DISC WITH A 100-LB DISC, REPLACED THE STEAM CAP ON THE BOTTOM OF THE CAR, AND RELEASED THE CAR TO PROCEED TO ITS DESTIANATION.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: DRIVER/DOCKMAN GREG HEBEL BEGAN WORKING TRAILER 206044 AT 4:00AM 7/22. THIS PAIL WAS ON TRAILER FLOOR ALONG WALL & WAS THE ONLY ITEM ON PRO #11916827.  AS HE WALKED OFF WITH IT HE FELT LIQUID SPLASH ON HIS PANTS & HIS LEG BURNED A LITTLE.  HE THEN NOTICED THAT A ROAD DRIVER HAD PUT GRIT IN THE TRAILER TO ABSORB WHAT HE THEN SAW TO BE A PUNCTURE ON THE UPPER THIRD SIDE OF THIS PAIL FROM WHENCE SOME LEAKAGE HAD ACCURRED. UNFORTUNATELY, I NEGLECTED TO TAKE A PICTURE OF THIS PAIL BEFORE RETURNING IT TO THE SHIPPER IN A RECOVERY DRUM FOR CREDIT.  THE PAIL APPEARED TO HAVE BEEN ABRADED BY ANOTHER FLAT METAL OBJECT AS IT BORE SCRAPE MARKS TO THE POINT OF WHERE THE ACTUAL PUNCTURE OCCURRED.  THE PUNCTURE WAS THIN AND SELF-SEALED AFTER SETTING ON OUR DOCK AWAITING DISPOSITION, BUT IT WAS ABVIOUS THAT CONTENTS HAD LEAKED AND EATEN THE LABEL ON THEIR WAY TO THE FLOOR.  THE GRIT ON THE TRAILER FLOOR WAS ANOTHER CLUE THAT SOMEONE KNEW WE HAD A PROBLEM HERE.

ON 26 JULY 1991 OUR DRIVER LOADED THE DEVICE ON THE VAN AT SHIPPERS LOCATION AND DROVE THE LOAD BACK TO THE FONTANNA TERMINAL.  AT THE TERMINAL THE ORIGINAL DRIVER UNHOOKED FROM THE TRAILER AND LEFT IT IN A SECURE AREA.  ON 28 JULY 1991 THE SECOND DRIVER, FRANCES GOODE HOOKED ONTO THE TRAILER WITH THE DEVICE.  WHILE INSPECTING THE TRUCK AND TRAILER DRIVER NOTICED A HISSING SOUND AND FOUL IRRITATING ODOR.  THE DRIVER THEN NOTIFIED PROPER AUTHORITIES.  THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL EVACUATED UP TO 12 PEOPLE IN THE AREA.  THE DRIVER WAS TREATED AT THE SCENE.  THE DEVICE WAS RESECURED AND THE SHIPMENT WAS ALLOWED TO CONTINUE.  ON CLOSE INSPECTION IT WAS FOUND THAT A PRESSURE LINE FROM THE "SCRUB TANK" TO A PRESSURE MONITORING GAUGE HAD COME LOOSE. FOR TECHNICAL INFORMATION ON THE MOLECULAR SCRUBBER PLEASE CALL THE SHIPPER'S TECHNICAL ENGINEER: RUBIN MARRUJO (805) 866-3035  (805) 866-0570

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: THE DRIVER WAS UNLOADING THE GASOLINE PRODUCT INTO A 1,000 GAL CAPACITY UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK THAT IS LOCATED OUT OF SITE OF THE DRIVER BEHIND A PORTABLE BUILDING ON SITE.  THE DRIVER HEARD THE TANK FILLING, SAW PRODUCT OVERFLOW AND IMMEDIATELY CLOSED THE FLOW OF PRODUCT, SPILLING APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS ONTO THE CONCRETE SURFACE.  THE STATION ATTENDANT, TYLER BROWN, WASHED THE SPILLED PRODUCT WITH A WATER HOSE INTO A DRAIN AS DRIVER WAS ON THE PHONE REPORTING THE INCIDENT TO HIS TERMINAL SUPERVISOR, JIM ADAMS.

column42: HYDROGEN PEROXIDE, STABILIZED OR HYDROGEN PEROXIDE AQUEOUS SOLUTIONS, STABILIZED WITH MORE THAN 60 PERCENT HYDROGEN PEROXIDE
column168: RECEIVED A CALL THAT GATX 73788 WAS ON FIRE.  I CONTACTED LARRY MAYBELLY OF OP&C, AND HE UNDERSTOOD THAT THE TANK CAR WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP AND PRODUCT HAD SPILLED ON THE GROUND AND STARTED SMOLDERING.  THE INITIAL REPORT FROM SYLVIA TRENIN WAS THAT THE TANK CAR WAS A LOAD OF HYDROGEN PEROXIDE, & 52% SOLUTION WITH A STCC OF 4918335.  LARRY MAYBELLY CONFIRMED THIS INFORMATION AND ALSO GAVE ME A SHIPPER CONTACT FOR FMC, MR. NEIL SECRIST.  MR. SECRIST ADVISED ME THAT BILL ZMEKO OF FMC NEWARK WAS RESPONDING TO THE SCENE. I MADE CONTACT WITH SP POLICE IN OAKLAND AND REQUESTED THEY DISPATCH AN OFFICER TO THE SCENE.  WAS ADVISED THAT OFFICER TORRES WAS ENROUTE. 1250 HOURS: LARRY MAYBELLY ADVISED ME THAT THE FIRE WAS OUT, AND DUE TO A VAPOR CLOUD, A PORTION OF I-880 WAS CLOSED.  CONTACT FOR THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CHIEF ANDERSON. 2305 HOURS: MADE CONTACT WITH CHIEF ANDERSON.  HE CONFIRMED THAT THE CAR WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR AND HAD STARTED A SMALL FIRE ON THE TIES.  AT THE TIME OF THIS CALL,. HE STATED THAT THE FIRE WAS OUT AND THAT HE HAD SENT IN A TEAM FOR FINAL ASSESSMENT. HE ALSO STATED THAT A PORTION OF MISSION BLVD. AND I-880 HAD BEEN CLOSED DUE TO A VAPOR CLOUD THAT WAS RELEASED WHEN THE FIRE WAS PUT OUT.  AN EMT CHECK POINT HAD BEEN SET-UP FOR ANYONE NEEDING MEDICAL ATTENTION. AT THE TIME OF THIS CALL, HE STATED THAT HE WAS DOWN GRADING THE EMERGENCY.  I ADVISED HIM THAT BILL ZMEKO OF FMC AND MIKE GRANT FOR SP WAS IN RESPONSE TO THE SCENE TO PROVIDE ASSISTANCE. WAS ADVISED BY MIKE GRANT THAT THERE WAS NO PRODUCT ON THE GROUND AND THAT BILL ZMEKO OF FMC REPLACED THE RUPTURED DISC AND RELEASED THE CAR TO FMC, NEWARK, CA.

TANK CAR UTLX 27659 DERAILED DURING SWITCHING OPERATIONS, STRIKING ACFX 86231 STANDING IN THE LOADING TRACK.  TANK CAR ACFX 86231 WAS BEING PRESSURIZED FOR LOADING.  TRANSFER PIPES/HOSES WERE BROKEN LOOSE WHICH ALLOWED RELEASE OF CHLORINE GAS.  PIONEER CHLORO ALKALI PERSONNEL RESPONDED AND SECURED THE TRANSFER CONNECTIONS WHICH STOPPED RELEASE OF GAS.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: ON 07/19/91, SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) G.B. REEDER WAS NOTIFIED THAT PLMX 27121 WAS LEAKING.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED ON AN INDUSTRIAL SPUR.  SSA/HM REEDER RESPONDED AND INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE SEAL BETWEEN THE MANWAY COVER PLATE AND THE FLANGE ON THE TANK WAS LEAKING.  THE SEAL WAS STUFFED WITH LEAD WOOD AND SILICON AND WRAPPED TO STOP THE LEAK.  THE CAR WAS THEN MOVED TO OCCIDENTAL CHEMICAL FOR DE-PRESSURIZATION.  CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED.
